# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fielding-cricket
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] The **2005 Ashes series** was that year's edition of the long-standing cricket rivalry between England and Australia.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] Starting on 21 July 2005, England and Australia played five Tests, with the Ashes held by Australia as the most recent victors.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] The final result was a 2–1 series win for England, who succeeded (for the first time since 1986–87) in their biennial attempt to win the urn.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] In March 2005, Australia captain Ricky Ponting said this Ashes series would be the closest since Australia's dominance began in 1989.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] Since 1989, when Australia started their winning Ashes streak, England had lost by more than one match in all but one of the series played, that of 1997.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] However, since the previous series in 2002–03, England had improved on their fifth place in the official rankings, and were second before this series.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] Australia were still top-ranked, but England had won 14 and drawn three of their 18 previous Test matches since March 2004, and had won six successive series.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] Nonetheless, before the First Test some Australians, including fast bowler Glenn McGrath, were suggesting that a 5–0 win in the series for Australia was a serious possibility.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] On the day after the series it was "hailed as the most thrilling series ever".
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] Three matches in particular were very closely fought, with one match decided by a two-run margin, one match drawn with only one wicket remaining, and one match won by three wickets.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] The outcome of the contest was not decided until the last day of the series.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] Australia won the first Test comfortably, but in the second Test at Edgbaston, considered to be one of the greatest of all time, England levelled the series with a two-run victory, the narrowest win in Ashes history.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] The third Test ended in a draw (with England one wicket away from a win), and England won the fourth Test in Nottingham (Trent Bridge) by three wickets, losing seven men in a chase of 129, after England enforced the follow-on after gaining a lead of 259 on first innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] The fifth and final Test started on 8 September, at the Oval in London.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] It entered its final day with England batting in their second innings, 40 runs ahead with nine wickets in hand.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] Australia needed a win to force a 2–2 series draw and retain the Ashes; any other result would give the Ashes to England and end 16 years and eight series of Australian dominance.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] After a day of fluctuating fortunes, England established a lead of 341 after Kevin Pietersen's maiden century of 158 runs, and Australia batted for one over before the teams went off for bad light, and the match was declared a draw, ensuring the return of the Ashes to England.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] a Collingwood was added on 1 August for the second Test, but sent back to his county on 3 August.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] b An injury to Simon Jones saw Anderson come into the squad for the fifth Test, while Tremlett was dropped because he was "not on top of his game" according to England's chairman of selectors David Graveney.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p01] c Clark was called up as cover for pace bowlers McGrath and Lee before the third Test.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] The first day of cricket at Lord's saw 17 of the total of 40 wickets fall, and though Australia lost 10 of them, the BBC saw it as "advantage Australia".
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Ricky Ponting won the toss and chose to bat, and Steve Harmison shook up the opening batters early on, hitting the Australians with bouncers; the second ball of the match hit Justin Langer on the elbow but he went on to make 40 and top score for Australia.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] The pitch offered bounce and swing from the start, while Matthew Hoggard got a ball on line to swing between Matthew Hayden's bat and pad and into his off stump.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Hayden was gone for 12, having, according to the BBC report, "played nervously from the word go".
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Australia still scored at a rate above 4.5 runs per over in the mini-session before drinks, which was taken when Harmison cut Ponting on the right cheek, and in his next over Harmison got his first wicket of the series as Ponting edged him to Andrew Strauss at third slip for 9.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Langer was next to depart, having scored at above five an over when he top-edged a pull shot to Harmison at square-leg for 40 off the bowling of Andrew Flintoff, whose first over in Ashes cricket was a wicket maiden.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] In the next over, Simon Jones was brought on, he got an immediate reward, with Damien Martyn caught behind for 2, and in the penultimate over before lunch Michael Clarke was leg before wicket (lbw) to Jones, leaving Australia five down after the first session of play.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Adam Gilchrist, Simon Katich and Shane Warne all played a part in getting Australia past 100, forging innings in the 20s, but Flintoff had Gilchrist for 26 before Warne and Katich added 49 for the seventh wicket.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Harmison, coming back for a second spell, was wicketless in his first two overs but after drinks he took four wickets for seven runs in 2.2 overs as Australia were all out for 190.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] He finished with five wickets for 43 runs.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Glenn McGrath was the not out batter, ending with 10 runs, and he also opened the bowling with Brett Lee.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] England batted for six overs until tea without losing a wicket, scoring 10 runs, but McGrath, who bowled his usual accurate line and length, reaped the rewards after tea.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Marcus Trescothick fell first ball after tea, edging to slip to become McGrath's 500th victim in Test cricket, and Strauss fell in similar fashion three balls later.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Michael Vaughan and Ian Bell survived six overs, adding seven runs before McGrath had them bowled in the 13th and 15th over respectively.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] With Flintoff bowled by McGrath in the 17th, and England had lost five wickets for 21 runs, with five of their top six batters out in single figures.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] However, Kevin Pietersen and Geraint Jones batted together to make England's highest partnership of the innings, adding 58 and, according to the BBC report, "treating Jason Gillespie with some disdain".
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] A short ball from Lee was too much for Geraint Jones, though, and he fended it to wicket-keeper Gilchrist, out for 30.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Ashley Giles hit two quick boundaries to bat out the over, but the last ball of Lee's next over was glanced to the keeper, and Giles was out for 11, and England were 92/7 overnight – needing 98 for the last three wickets to get level with Australia.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] England cut the deficit on the second morning, but were still bowled out before they could build a first-innings lead.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Hoggard departed for a 16-ball duck, cutting a delivery from Warne to Hayden in the slips.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Pietersen now started to attack, taking 21 runs off seven deliveries before he was out caught by Martyn, a diving catch just inside the boundary, and England were nine down for 122, still trailing by 68.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] The English 10th wicket pairing of Simon Jones and Harmison added 33 after that, a stand that was the fifth-highest of the game thus far and which reduced Australia's lead to 35 runs.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] In the field, England started by having Langer run out for 6 in the fifth over, but Hayden and Ponting rebuilt to bat until lunch unbeaten.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Though Hayden was bowled by Flintoff for 34 three overs after lunch, the batters from three to six all passed 40; it was to be the only time in the series that Australia accomplished this feat.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Clarke needed an extra life to do it, but made England pay after Pietersen dropped him on 21, and thus the partnership was allowed to last for 34.3 overs, with 155 runs being scored.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Flintoff was smashed to all corners, with 84 runs being scored off him in his 19 second-day overs, but in the last 10 overs England came back to take wickets.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Started by an inside-edge from Clarke off Hoggard, which left Australia's 24-year-old batter bowled for 91, and Australia lost a further three wickets for 24 runs before the end of the day.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] The Australian lead was still 314, twice England's first innings total and then some, and Katich was still batting, not out on 10.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Four overs into the morning, specialist spin bowler Giles was involved in a dismissal for the only time in the match, having Lee run out for 8.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] However, Gillespie batted for an hour and 15 minutes, and took part in a 52-run stand with the recognised batter, Katich before Simon Jones got his reward with an away-swinger that crashed into Gillespie's off stump, after having three catches dropped.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] The last-wicket partnership rubbed it in with 43 more runs before Katich was caught by Simon Jones off Harmison, but England were set what would be a world record 420 to win.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] They started positively, riding some favourable umpiring decisions; Aleem Dar turned down four strong lbw appeals off Warne.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Strauss and Trescothick could thus add 80 for the first wicket before Strauss edged a short ball from Lee back into the bowler's waiting hands.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Vaughan got off the mark with a four with his second ball, before facing 24 dot balls in the next three-quarters of an hour.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Meanwhile, wickets fell at the other end, as Trescothick departed for 44, edging a straight ball from Warne to first slip after having taken him for 10 in the previous over, and Bell was out LBW to a ball that did not turn.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Rain frustrated both Australia and neutral fans who wanted to see cricket played on the morning of the fourth day, but at 15:45 BST the rain relented and the covers were taken off.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Then, it took 10 overs for Australia to wrap up England's innings, McGrath taking four of the five wickets required and Warne the last; Giles, Hoggard, Harmison and Simon Jones were all dismissed for ducks, and England could only cut 24 runs off Australia's eventual win margin of 239.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Twenty-two of those fourth-day runs came from Pietersen who was left stranded on an unbeaten 64 to have a Test batting average of 121 after his first match.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] The psychological battles before the match included many Australian statements to the press about how the pitch "played into [their] hands", that England had been "spending too much time talking", and that their top order had been "taking bad options".
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] It was also suggested that the team that won the toss should choose to bowl first to stand the best chance of victory, as had happened in 12 of the 13 Tests at Edgbaston since 1991.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] An hour before the first ball was bowled, Australian seam bowler Glenn McGrath tore the ligaments in his ankle after treading on a stray cricket ball while playing rugby during a pre-match warm-up.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Michael Kasprowicz took McGrath's place in the team.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Ricky Ponting won the toss and opted to bowl, but Jonathan Agnew of the BBC claimed "it was clear that his decision had backfired" once England started batting, a view supported by Channel 4 analyst Simon Hughes.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] England took advantage of being inserted and came back strongly, becoming the first team to hit 400 runs in a first day of Test cricket against Australia since 1938.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] The English scored at a pace above four an over in their opening partnership between Marcus Trescothick, who hit nine boundaries off Brett Lee, and Andrew Strauss, who scored freely off Jason Gillespie and Kasprowicz.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Their 112-run partnership was the highest by England in the series thus far; the Australians had only surpassed that once, through Damien Martyn and Michael Clarke's 155 at Lord's.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Although Warne produced an outstanding delivery to dismiss Strauss bowled for 48, to add to Australia's woes, Trescothick was caught off a no-ball on 32, and eventually went on to make 90, being the second man out shortly after lunch, with the score 164/2 after 32.3 overs.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] In the next five overs, England lost both Ian Bell, who notched up his third successive single-figure score, and Michael Vaughan, who pulled a short Gillespie delivery to the hands of Lee, but that did little to slow the scoring rate.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] 132 runs had been taken in the morning session; the afternoon yielded 157.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Kevin Pietersen, in his second Test match, hit ten fours and one six, and made a 103-run partnership in 105 balls with Andrew Flintoff.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Flintoff scored 68 off 62 balls, and Lee's 18 balls of the afternoon session were taken for 26 runs, including two sixes.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Lee bowled just 17 overs in England's first innings, and conceded 111 runs, but got the wicket of Pietersen, who pulled to Simon Katich for 71 off 76 balls, and with the score on 342/7 with 24 scheduled overs remaining in the day.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Steve Harmison then smacked two fours and a six in a 15-minute cameo worth 17 runs, and Simon Jones stuck around with Matthew Hoggard for a last-wicket partnership of 32, Jones making 19 not out.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Shane Warne finally got the better of Hoggard, to end with four wickets for 116, but by that time, England had ended their innings on 407 all out in just under 80 overs.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Just as Australia's opening batters walked out and prepared for their innings, rain began to fall on Edgbaston and play had to be stopped.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] England's bowlers started well when Harmison bowled a maiden over first up to Justin Langer, and Matthew Hayden drove Harmison's new-ball partner Hoggard to short mid-off for a golden duck – the first of Hayden's Test career.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Ponting and Langer then hit runs just as quickly as England had done, before the umpire's finger went up twice more before lunch; Ponting swept a shot off Ashley Giles to the opposing captain Vaughan for 61, and Martyn was run out taking a single for 20, again by Vaughan.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Langer and Clarke continued after lunch in the same vein, hitting 76 runs in an hour and a half, but a couple of wickets within five overs took Australia to 208/5, needing 199 for the last five wickets for parity.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] The partnership between Langer and Adam Gilchrist saw them to tea with no further loss.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Meanwhile, Giles' return of 3/78, including Ponting, Clarke and Warne, was to be his best bowling figures all series.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] England began their second innings with a 99-run lead and looked to continue their aggressive batting intent to build their lead before stumps on day 2.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] After Trescothick and Strauss had hit five boundaries in six overs and taken the second innings total to 25 for 0, Ponting brought on Warne in the seventh over.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Warne broke through with his second ball of the innings with arguably one of the best deliveries of the series by any bowler.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Nightwatchman Hoggard survived four balls to end the day, when England held a lead of 124 runs, with nine wickets in hand.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Pietersen survived what looked like an edge from the first ball he faced, and went on to make 20 before he was given out in a similar situation from Warne.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] His 41-run partnership with Bell took England's lead past 150, but despite having batted for over an hour, Bell still needed 29 more for his half-century when he gave a tiny edge to Gilchrist.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] England's last recognised batting pair, between Flintoff and wicket-keeper Geraint Jones, saw England to lunch, but Flintoff had suffered an injury to his left shoulder and looked in obvious pain, and Jones departed shortly after lunch.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Giles lasted longer, batting through 45 minutes before he was caught by Hayden, and Harmison faced one delivery to leave England at 131/9.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Simon Jones and Flintoff carried on, however.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Jones managed 12 runs in his 42-minute stay at the crease while Flintoff took Lee for 33 off the 28 balls he faced from the Australian paceman.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Flintoff also took runs off Kasprowicz, with his third over yielding 20 runs for England, including a couple of no-balls.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] At one point during Flintoff's innings, Ponting had nine men on the boundary, with only the bowler and wicket-keeper inside the circle.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] However, Flintoff hit a six over them, too, and another of his sixes landed on top of the stands.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Flintoff ended with 73, as the only man to pass 25 for England, before he was bowled by Warne.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Warne finished with figures of 6/46 from 23.1 overs, having bowled unchanged from the seventh over to the end.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] The all-rounder proceeded to bowl the over of the series; although he failed to complete the hat-trick he was on from the previous innings, with his second ball he bowled Langer with a leg cutter.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] His third delivery was narrowly turned down for lbw, the fourth found Ponting's edge but failed to carry to slip, an lbw appeal on the fifth was also turned down, and his sixth, which Ponting left outside the off stump, was a no-ball, allowing him an extra delivery.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Flintoff produced another leg cutter, Ponting edged his drive and was out caught behind.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Including the previous innings, Flintoff had taken four wickets in nine balls.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] But more importantly, Australia had been reduced from 47/0 to 48/2.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Hayden kept going, and his dismissal came in an over where Australia had taken eight runs from the first four balls; however, Simon Jones got the last laugh on Hayden, only to later be reprimanded and fined by the International Cricket Council for his celebrations.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] England kept on the pressure, getting three more wickets before the scheduled close of play: Giles dismissed Katich and Gilchrist, and an in-swinging ball from Flintoff took care of Gillespie, who was trapped lbw.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] An extra half-hour of play was allowed, as a result was nearing, but Warne and Clarke defied the English bowling attack.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Warne "took the attacking approach", and took on Giles for 12 in one over.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] He ended on 20 not out overnight, as Warne and Clarke batted together for 40 minutes before Harmison, bowling his third spell of the day, brought the third day's proceedings to an end with a slower ball that was not read correctly by Clarke, who missed the ball completely to be bowled.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Mark Nicholas, in live commentary, described the delivery as "...one of the great balls.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Given the moment, given the batsman and given the match, that is a staggering gamble that has paid off for Harmison.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] He bowled it perfectly." The third day saw a total of 17 wickets fall, and England needed just two wickets for victory, while Australia still needed 107 runs.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] England were said to be "on the brink of...victory", but Australia came back thanks to two partnerships worth more than 40 to take themselves within three runs of a 2–0 series lead.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] First, Warne and Lee added 45 for the ninth wicket, before Warne trod on his own stumps after a full Flintoff ball and was out hit wicket.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Kasprowicz came in and supported Lee well, fending off aggressive bowling from Flintoff and Harmison, and Simon Jones dropped a difficult chance at third man to remove Kasprowicz with 15 left to get.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] With Australia edging towards victory, taking the pragmatic and sensible approach of preferring singles to risky boundaries, England were now bowling aggressive short balls at the tail-enders, hoping for short catches or to surprise the batters with yorkers.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] With four runs needed to win, Lee drove Harmison's attempted yorker towards the cover-point boundary, where it was fielded; it was timed so well that had Lee placed it five yards either team of the fielder's initial position, it would have likely won Australia the match.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] The batters crossed for a single, leaving three runs to win with the weaker batter Kasprowicz on strike.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Harmison delivered another short ball, which Kasprowicz fended off and Geraint Jones took an athletic catch down the leg side.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] England appealed, and Kasprowicz was given out caught by Bowden.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] England's two-run victory was the narrowest win (by runs) in Ashes cricket history to date (there had been two Ashes Tests won by a margin of only three runs).
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] It was also the second narrowest margin of victory in Test cricket history behind only the West Indies' victory by a single run over Australia in Adelaide in 1993, which was later matched by New Zealand's one-run win over England in Wellington in 2023.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] With the series square after England's close win in the second match at Edgbaston in Birmingham, neither team could secure the series win after the third Test at Old Trafford in Manchester, so there was still all to play for.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] After naming an unchanged line-up, England were immediately faced by the pairing of Glenn McGrath and Brett Lee.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] There were doubts about whether they could play before the match started, because of the injuries they had sustained earlier, but they both passed fitness tests.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Though Andrew Strauss succumbed in the 10th over, England lost no further wickets before lunch, and only one more before tea.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] There were many missed opportunities for Australia, who dropped Trescothick, Michael Vaughan (twice) and Ian Bell on the first day, which helped Trescothick and Vaughan to get a partnership of 137 before Trescothick was dismissed after lunch.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Vaughan powered on, making his hundred after 206 minutes to become the first man in the series to get a century.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Having made 166 runs, an innings described as "majestic", Vaughan eventually hit Simon Katich straight to McGrath at the boundary, but had still made what was to be the highest individual score in the series.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Together with Vaughan, Australia were also faced with a more defiant Bell, who had not passed 25 in his four first innings in the series, but made 59 before the day ended.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Picking up where Vaughan left off, Bell, Kevin Pietersen and nightwatchman Matthew Hoggard closed out the day for England with the scoreboard reading 341/5, with Lee adding two wickets to the tally before the end of the day.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Bell did not add to his overnight score, being given out caught behind in controversial circumstances, as replays indicated any contact with the ball involved neither bat nor glove.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Following a brief rain interval England then lost two more wickets just before lunch, Andrew Flintoff after scoring a quick-fire 46 and Geraint Jones for 42.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] After lunch Australia quickly dispatched the remaining two wickets for just a further 10 runs, bowling England out for a score of 444, with McGrath finishing on his worst-ever Test figures of 0/86.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Australia started their innings tentatively with Hoggard dropping a low catch from Matthew Hayden off his own bowling.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Just before tea Australia lost their first wicket with Hayden out caught at short leg from Ashley Giles first over.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] After tea Australia lost another couple of wickets, Ricky Ponting caught for seven and Hayden given out lbw for 34.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Gilchrist put on 30 before edging the first ball of Simon Jones' spell to Geraint Jones.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] This brought in Michael Clarke who had been recuperating at the team hotel after damaging his back on the first day.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Owing to this injury, Clarke needed Hayden to act as a runner.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Warne made inroads with the bat, just as at Edgbaston four days previously, but Clarke only managed to add seven runs before being deceived by a reverse-swinging delivery from Simon Jones.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Warne and Jason Gillespie saw the day out with Warne finishing on 45 not out.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] The day finished with Australia on 214/7, 230 behind and needing another 31 runs to avoid a follow-on.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] The score was adjusted from 210 overnight owing to one of the umpires failing to signal four byes.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Rain delayed the start of play until 16:00 BST, and even then only eight overs were possible before play was again suspended, although a further six overs were bowled later on before yet more rain meant that play was abandoned for the day.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Australia closed on 264/7, still 180 in arrears, but England probably felt that they missed several opportunities to put the game beyond their opponents.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Having been hampered by a rain-shortened day three, the Australians were ready to put more wood to the ball on day four, and they did not disappoint.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Warne continued his march towards his maiden Test century before holing out with a hook shot to a well-placed Giles at 90.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Simon Jones mopped up the other two wickets to bowl Australia out for 302, Jones finishing the innings with a career best figures of 6/53.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Knowing that scoring runs quickly was the only chance they had at winning the match with so much of the previous day's play washed out, England took the fight to the Australians in their second innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] The opening partnership of Strauss and Trescothick scored 26 before the lunch interval, but Trescothick played on to be bowled after scoring 41, giving McGrath his first wicket of the match.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Strauss, however, compiled a fine century, his sixth from just 17 matches, scoring 106 before getting out caught.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Gilchrist missed two stumping opportunities to remove Bell and failing to hold a catch to remove Flintoff.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Bell capitalised on Gilchrist's errors, partnering Strauss for 28 overs and recording a well-deserved 65.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Although wickets continued to fall, England were more concerned about scoring quickly than staying at the crease.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Trescothick, Strauss and Bell all scored with a strike rate of over 63, and Geraint Jones added 27 runs off just 12 balls before England declared on 280/6 to give them a spell at Australia in the evening and a chance of winning the match the next day.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] McGrath recorded another five-wicket haul in an innings, but was expensive, giving away 115 runs.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Warne, despite bowling 25 overs, failed to take a wicket, recording figures of 0/74.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Australia needed 423 to win, which would be a record fourth innings total to win a match.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Australia saw out the last 10 overs without losing a wicket and put on 24 runs.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] This left the match on a knife edge, with all three results still possible.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p02] Australia required 399 runs on the final day to win from a possible 98 overs, while England still needed to take all 10 Australian second innings wickets.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Given the performances of the England bowling attack at Edgbaston and in the first innings of this match, English hopes of a win were high.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Queues began at 06:00 and by 08:40, more than two hours before the first ball was due to be bowled, the Old Trafford staff closed the gates to the stadium.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] 20,000 people were left disappointed in addition to the 23,000-capacity crowd.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The day started poorly for them with Justin Langer falling for 14 on the seventh ball of the day, nicking a ball delivered by Hoggard behind to Geraint Jones.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Australia captain Ricky Ponting was brought to the crease to steady the ship, and he narrowly survived being run out early on.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] This proved crucial in the context of the match, as the momentum gradually swung in Australia's direction.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Michael Clarke provided stouter resistance in a cameo of 39 before a complete misjudgement led him to shoulder arms to a Simon Jones delivery which reverse-swung back into his off stump, sending it cartwheeling backwards.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] This order change, however, did not work: Gillespie lasted just five balls before being trapped plumb lbw off Hoggard for a duck, leaving Australia 264/7, and England now needing just three wickets from the final 31 overs to win the match and go 2–1 up in the series.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Ponting, however, remained as composed and secure as ever, reaching his first and only century of the series.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Together with Warne, who continued to frustrate the England bowlers, they added 76 runs for the eighth wicket.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Pietersen missed a chance to dismiss Warne, putting down a difficult chance at short midwicket off a Jones full toss, and with 9.5 overs left in the match, England still needed three wickets and Australia required 83 runs.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Warne was then finally out in remarkable circumstances, as Strauss put down a regulation catch at second slip off the bowling of Flintoff, only for the ball to rebound off his right thigh.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Geraint Jones flung himself to his right to take a one-handed catch just above the ground.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Ponting battled on, passing 150, but having spent over seven hours at the crease in a single day, his concentration began to waver and he finally succumbed to Steve Harmison, strangled down the leg side for a remarkable innings of 156 that was good enough to earn him man of the match honours.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Glenn McGrath was once again ruled out because of injury, this time to his elbow, and Australia also dropped the out-of-form Jason Gillespie, leaving them with a seam attack of Brett Lee, debutant Shaun Tait and Michael Kasprowicz.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] England, having been on top in the last two Tests, were unchanged.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] England won the toss and chose to bat, and they got off to a strong start.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Boosted by no-balls from the seamers – a total of 18 before lunch – Marcus Trescothick and Andrew Strauss scored runs quickly and easily, and enjoyed batting on a pitch which gave the bowlers no aid.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] They recorded their second 100-run opening partnership of the series, before Strauss was freakishly dismissed for 35, sweeping Shane Warne onto his boot and into Matthew Hayden's waiting hands at slip – a wicket confirmed by the third umpire.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Michael Vaughan continued on his fine form from Old Trafford, though, punishing bad balls from Lee to go into lunch with his score on 14.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Trescothick, meanwhile, rode his luck, as he was bowled off a no-ball on 55, much to Lee's displeasure.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Only 3.1 overs were possible in the afternoon session, owing to rain.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Coming back after tea, England immediately lost two wickets to Tait, who used the cloud cover to good effect and swung the ball well.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] However, Vaughan and Kevin Pietersen batted well together for a 67-run partnership, although they were each dropped once.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Towards the end of the day, Ricky Ponting brought himself on, and his medium pace yielded a wicket – that of Vaughan for 58.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Overnight, the match was evenly poised with England 229/4.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Australia dismissed Pietersen at the beginning of the morning's play, edging a full outswinger from Lee through to wicket-keeper Adam Gilchrist, leaving England at 241/5; however, an unbeaten century partnership from Andrew Flintoff and Geraint Jones took England's score to 344/5 at lunch.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] After the interval, the pair continued to score quickly for another hour, and extended their partnership to 177 before Flintoff was lbw to Tait for 102, his first Test century against Australia.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The loss of Flintoff did not deter the English, as Jones continued to hit runs through the off side on the way to his highest score against the Australians, making 85 before he was caught and bowled by Kasprowicz.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The next two wickets fell quickly, but a stubborn last-wicket partnership of 23 between Matthew Hoggard and Simon Jones – including an incident where the ball hit the stumps but the bails failed to fall off – saw England to 477 all out at tea.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] In the evening session, England's bowlers, especially Hoggard, managed to find much more swing than the Australian bowlers had done, and ripped through the Australian top order.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The first three wickets fell in a crucial period of 11 balls (although the third, which dismissed Damien Martyn lbw, was a poor decision – television replays indicated that the ball hit the bat before the body).
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] By the close of play, Australia had been reduced to 99/5 to complete a successful day for England.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Katich and Gilchrist decided that attack was the best form of defence, adding 58 in only 8.5 overs in the morning, before England came back to take the next four wickets for the addition of only 18 runs, leaving Australia perilously placed at 175/9.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Simon Jones was the main culprit, using swing to good effect as he removed Katich and Warne in successive balls, and then had Kasprowicz clean-bowled.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Lee added 47 in 44 balls, including three huge sixes, to take Australia's score to 218, before he was caught off Jones' bowling to give Jones his fifth wicket of the innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Despite their aggressive batting, Australia therefore finished the first innings 259 runs behind.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Vaughan then took a huge gamble by forcing the visitors to follow on (the first time Australia had followed on in 17 years and 190 Tests, as they had not been made to follow on since facing Pakistan in Karachi in 1988).
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Vaughan's decision made a draw far less likely, but in an almost Australian style of ruthlessness, it was clear that England were not going to be cowed by the visitors' reputation: they were playing to win.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Australia began their second innings very positively; they safely reached 14 without loss before the lunch break, and then powered on in the afternoon session, adding 100 more runs before tea, and only losing Hayden for 26.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] For England, the afternoon session was their worst of the match; to compound their misery, Simon Jones showed signs of injury, and Strauss dropped Justin Langer on 38.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] In the evening session, England fought back and managed to take three wickets, but also dropped a catch and missed a stumping.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Australia finished the day still 37 runs in arrears but with only six wickets in hand.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Simon Jones also went off the field during the evening session with an ankle injury, and was taken to hospital for a scan.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] While Jones was off the field receiving attention, specialist substitute fielder Gary Pratt ran out Australia captain Ponting.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] As he left the field, Ponting expressed his displeasure to the England dressing room at their frequent use of subs during the series, allegedly to keep their key bowlers fresh.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Day Four began in earnest with Michael Clarke and Katich continuing their partnership from the previous day.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] However, Katich had already twice flirted with dismissal, saved only by chance both times.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] England's lead slowly evaporated without a wicket falling, but Hoggard's taking of Clarke's and then Gilchrist's scalps on either side of the lunch break swung the initiative back into England's hands.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The injury to Simon Jones became somewhat obvious as the pacers struggled to capture the magic that Jones had created the previous day that had forced Australia to follow on.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Despite this, the Australian run rate remained low as both teams stared each other down.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Mistakes by Geraint Jones and Pietersen were quickly nullified by the dismissal of Warne for 45 and Kasprowicz for 19, and after a few overs' resistance, Tait was bowled middle stump for 4 and Australia were all out for 387.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Although this score was the most runs the Australian batting line-up scored in any innings in the series, it left England requiring just 129 runs to win the match, well short of Shane Warne's target of 170.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Trescothick started the chase positively, scoring 27 from 22 balls and helping England to 32 without loss in just 5 overs.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] With Kasprowicz conceding 19 runs from his first two (and what would turn out to be only) overs in the innings, knowing he had little option without McGrath in his bowling line-up, Ponting brought Warne on to bowl in the hopes that he could somehow seize the initiative.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Warne struck with his very first ball, having Trescothick caught at silly point, before removing Vaughan, who was caught at slip for a six-ball duck, and then Strauss few overs later, caught at leg slip for 23.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Brett Lee complemented Warne with some aggressive, short-pitched bowling and had Bell caught in the deep after an ill-advised hook shot for just 3.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] From 32 without loss, England's top order had collapsed to 57/4 and the game was suddenly very much in the balance.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Flintoff and Pietersen rode their luck with some risky shots to edge England ever closer to their target with an invaluable partnership of 46, before Lee had Pietersen well caught by Gilchrist and then produced a jaffa to castle Flintoff and leave England at 111/6, still 18 runs short of victory.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Geraint Jones' dismissal by Warne for 3 left only three wickets remaining, and the tension was so great that every run at this point was met with an eruption of cheers from the Trent Bridge crowd.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Ashley Giles and Hoggard, under immense pressure, slowly chipped away at the required runs, before Hoggard hit a boundary off a Lee full-toss to leave England needing just four runs to win.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Warne was then mere millimetres away from having Giles clean-bowled in the next over, before Giles successfully guided England home by hitting the winning runs off Warne through midwicket.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Man of the match honours went to Flintoff for his first-innings century and crucial 26 second-innings runs.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] More importantly, however, this gave England a crucial 2–1 lead heading back to London for the fifth and final Test, ensuring that they could not lose the series; however, with the Ashes going to Australia in the event of a drawn series, there was still all to play for at The Oval.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Australia named Glenn McGrath, recovered from an elbow injury, to replace Michael Kasprowicz.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] England's Simon Jones did not recover from his ankle injury from the previous Test in time to be included in the England team, and was replaced after much speculation by all-rounder Paul Collingwood, in preference to specialist fast bowler James Anderson.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] With the fate of the Ashes urn on the line, the proverbial first blood was drawn by England as Michael Vaughan won his third toss of the series (much to the delight of the partisan Oval crowd).
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Vaughan elected to have his team bat first with the intent to try and bat Australia out of the game.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Certain forecasts for London called for showers sometime during the weekend, which, it was thought, might wipe up to a day of action or more from the ledger.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] If England could bat long and score heavily, it would make chances of an Australian victory almost impossible.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Marcus Trescothick and Andrew Strauss began with an 82-run partnership for the first wicket, but Shane Warne once again proved to be England's undoing.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Hayden took a fantastic low catch at slip to dismiss Trescothick for 43, while Vaughan gave away a soft dismissal by hitting a rare poor delivery from Warne straight to Clarke at midwicket for 11.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Bell fell to Warne shortly afterwards without scoring, and England went to lunch on 115/3.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Warne continued after lunch by taking his fourth wicket of the innings, clean-bowling Kevin Pietersen for 14 and leaving England in trouble at 131/4.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Andrew Flintoff emerged to form a vital partnership of 143 with Strauss, before to falling to McGrath for 72 an hour after tea.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Strauss, however, went on to pass 100, becoming the only player from either team to do so twice in the series.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Paul Collingwood, making his first appearance in an England Test for two years, made just 7 before being trapped lbw by a Tait yorker, before Strauss was dismissed late in the day for 129 by Warne off an acrobatic catch by Simon Katich.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The day ended with Geraint Jones and Ashley Giles at the crease, with England 319/7.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Day two began positively for the Australians, with Jones being bowled for 25 off Brett Lee and Matthew Hoggard managing a meagre 2 before being dismissed by McGrath.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] However, Giles and Steve Harmison frustrated the Australians by taking the score past 370, before Warne trapped Giles lbw shortly before midday, leaving England all out for 373.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The Australian first innings got off to a solid start, with Justin Langer forging a 100-partnership with fellow opener Matthew Hayden – the only opening-partnership century of the series by the Australians.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Langer played some blistering strokes off Giles' bowling in particular, but survived a sharp chance to Trescothick at first slip.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The Australians were offered the light immediately after tea, despite the English protesting and wanting to bowl Giles.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The Australians surprised many by accepting the umpires' offer – many thought that, given they needed to win the test to retain the Ashes, they would want to use as much time available for batting as possible – and the light never improved, with light rain coming down later.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Thus, the day concluded with Australia 112/0, still 261 runs behind England.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] After a delay for wet field conditions, the third day began with a flurry of action, as both Langer and Hayden had close calls with lbw appeals, which replays suggested should have been out, and shies at the stumps that just missed.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] However, no batter was given out in the morning session, where only 14 overs of play was possible, owing to rain.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] After lunch Hayden and Langer continued their solid batting, frustrating the England bowlers, with Langer reaching his 22nd Test century.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Shortly afterwards, England gained a minor victory as Harmison dismissed Langer, who departed to a rapturous ovation for 105.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Ricky Ponting should then have been dismissed for a bat-pad catch off Giles, but Bowden turned down the appeal.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Hayden also achieved three-figure success later in the day – his first century for over a year, while Flintoff's hostile and accurate bowling was rewarded with the wicket of Ponting, caught at slip by Strauss.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] With this wicket, Flintoff equalled Ian Botham's hitherto unique achievement of 300 runs and 20 wickets in an Ashes series.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Flintoff had a later appeal for a catch behind turned down by Rudi Koertzen, despite it hitting the bat.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The Australian batters once again surprisingly ended the day early by accepting another offer of bad light, bringing a much-interrupted day to a close after only 45.4 overs.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Thanks to dogged batting and at least four umpiring decisions in their favour on the third day, they finished 96 runs behind with eight wickets of their first innings intact on 277/2.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The fourth day started brightly for England, Damien Martyn hooking a short ball from Flintoff straight into the hands of Collingwood, in the third over of the day, having added only one to his overnight score of nine.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Flintoff's bowling led to further wickets, bringing Hayden's knock to an end as he was adjudged lbw, and he trapped Katich lbw the very next over for 1.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Taking into account his bowling the previous evening, Flintoff had bowled a remarkable spell of 18 overs in a row and claiming three key wickets in the process.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Hoggard then had Adam Gilchrist trapped in front LBW with an inswinger at the stroke of lunch.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Gilchrist, however, had added a quick 23 that could have proven vital, as Australia went into the pavilion 17 runs behind still with four wickets in hand.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] However, it only took six post-lunch overs for England to end the Australian effort.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Jones dropped a catch off Michael Clarke's bat, but it did not prove to be crucial, as Clarke was lbw to Hoggard in the next over.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Warne and McGrath both went for ducks, caught off a mistimed hook and in the slips respectively.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Finally Hoggard had Lee (6) caught in the deep and Australia were bowled out for 367.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Flintoff finished with 5/78 off 34 overs, the second five-for of his career, while Hoggard's 4/97 was his best return of the series.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Thus England, who had expected to begin their second innings chasing a hundred runs or more, were actually leading by six as they took up their bats in mid-afternoon.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Australia took a very quick wicket, that of Strauss, who was dismissed again by Warne, caught bat-and-pad by Katich for a solitary run.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The wicket was Warne's 167th against England, equalling Dennis Lillee's Ashes bowling record.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] 11 balls after this dismissal, umpires Rudi Koertzen and Billy Bowden judged it unfair to continue play, owing to inadequate light.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] One additional session of play was subsequently possible, taking England to a 40-run lead without further loss, before poor light ended the day with England at 34/1.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The fifth day began with the game still finely balanced.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] England's task was simple: bat out the day, and they would win the Ashes.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] In one final attempt to wrest the series from England's grip, Ponting put his trust in his two proven wicket-takers, McGrath and Warne.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Going into the day's play, both knew that this would be the last test match either man would play on English soil.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] England batted well for 40 minutes, with Vaughan taking the game to the Australian bowlers, but McGrath produced two beautiful deliveries in successive balls: Vaughan was first caught by a full-length, one-handed dive from Gilchrist for 45, before Ian Bell (for a pair) was caught at slip by Warne.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Despite the momentum having swung in the Australians' favour, their charge was not helped by a couple of dropped catches: first by Hayden at slip off the bowling of Warne, and then Warne putting down a simple chance at slip off Lee.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Warne, however, atoned for his errors, producing huge amounts of spin to give Trescothick all sorts of problems before finally trapping him lbw for 33, and then had Flintoff caught and bowled just before the lunch interval, leaving England 133 runs ahead with five wickets remaining.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Pietersen, meanwhile, continued to have near misses, narrowly beating a Michael Clarke run-out throw and having a Brett Lee bouncer hit his glove and balloon over the entire slip cordon.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] During the lunch break, Pietersen, who had been on the receiving end of some incredibly fast, aggressive short-pitched bowling from Lee before the interval, asked his captain Michael Vaughan how he should play the situation from here on in.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Pietersen took his captain at his word and proceeded to dispatch Lee to all parts of the ground, including launching him for two sixes over long leg and a baseball-like swat straight back past him for four.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] With support from Collingwood, Pietersen anchored the afternoon session almost single-handedly, reaching his maiden Test century just before tea.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Collingwood occupied the crease for over an hour before he was caught acrobatically at silly mid-off by Ponting for 10, but Jones was then bowled when he was deceived by a quick Shaun Tait delivery for just 1.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] England reached tea at 221/7 with a lead of 227, but with only three second-innings wickets remaining and still 49 overs left to be played, Australia were still very much in with a chance if they could take the last three wickets quickly.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] However, Pietersen and Giles combined for a stellar partnership of 109 in just 26 overs to take the game out of Australia's reach.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] In the 71st and 72nd overs, Pietersen flat-batted a 94.7 mph (152.4 km/h) bouncer from Brett Lee over the midwicket boundary for six, followed by depositing Warne back over his head for six a few balls later.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] In the wake of these two overs, Mark Nicholas on commentary remarked that "there's a sense now that the crowd are beginning to party".
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Giles, meanwhile, played the greatest innings of his Test career, hitting seven boundaries on his way to a score of 59 – the highest total he ever achieved in a Test innings – before Warne produced one final moment of magic and bowled Giles round his legs.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Harmison was caught at slip by Matthew Hayden just two balls later for a duck, and England were all out for 335.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] As the Australians began their innings with less than 19 overs left in the game, it was clear that not enough time remained for them to make up the 341 runs by which they trailed.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] They were offered the light after just four balls, and having accepted it, both teams had to return to the dressing rooms to wait for a formal finish.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] With the match effectively over, the crowd were eager for the Ashes to be presented to England, and the celebrations to begin.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] At 18:17 BST, after a period of some uncertainty and confusion, umpires Koertzen and Bowden removed the bails and pulled up the stumps to signal the end of the match.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Australia had scored just four leg byes in their second innings, making it the only innings in Test cricket history in which every run was an extra.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] With this fifth and final Test declared as a draw, England took the series 2–1, regaining the Ashes they had lost in 1989 and securing a first series win since 1986–87.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Pietersen, having scored his maiden Test century at such a crucial point in the match and series, was voted man of the match by Channel 4 viewers.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The new Compton–Miller Medal for the overall man of the series (as selected by each team's chairman of selectors, Trevor Hohns and David Graveney) was also presented to Flintoff.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Finally, the replica urn was presented to Vaughan, commemorating the home team's victory.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Political leaders like Prime Minister Tony Blair, Conservative leader Michael Howard and Liberal Democrat leader Charles Kennedy also sent their congratulations.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Blair stated that "By bringing the Ashes back after so long, you have given cricket a huge boost and lit up the whole summer".
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] "England's victory is historic, and I send hearty congratulations to the team...
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] It has been impossible not to get caught up by the excitement and sense of good will in the past few days," stated Kennedy.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] On the other end of the ledger, Australia's Prime Minister, John Howard (who was in New York for a UN summit and was given the bad news by an aide during a luncheon with the Asia Society) was gracious in his congratulations to England.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] "Look, there's natural disappointment but it's a situation where you give credit to the team that won," Howard stated, noting that there would not be a national day of mourning.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] "They will no doubt celebrate and that will be difficult for some, but that's the nature of these contests and we should not take anything away from England...They played very well.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Thousands of people also lined the streets along the parade route as the two buses made their way to Trafalgar Square.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] While the rest of the team simply enjoyed the sights, 5th Test Man-of-the-Match Kevin Pietersen sprayed champagne from the bus onto joyous revelers on the street, while wicketkeeper Geraint Jones held onto a Dalek doll with the words "Australians exterminated" attached to it.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] At Trafalgar Square, the crowd was treated to a victory celebration for both England teams, and before the ceremony closed the square broke into a rendition of "Jerusalem", which had become an unofficial hymn for the team during the 5th Test.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Interviews were carried out with all members of the men's team and Clare Connor, the captain of the women's team, by David Gower and Mark Nicholas, while the ceremony was broadcast live in the UK on BBC One, Channel 4 and Sky Sports News and around the world.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Afterwards, the team was entertained by the Prime Minister as guests of honour at 10 Downing Street, then returned the urn to its sacred home at Lord's for safekeeping.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Almost immediately criticism began in Australia; *The Sydney Morning Herald* immediately took issue with the fact that not only was captain Ricky Ponting out-thought by his opposite number Vaughan but the team was too old and simply did not score the runs when they were needed.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] *The Age* of Melbourne criticised the team for opening their big mouths once too often, hitting at Australia's earlier whitewash boast.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Psychological warfare, *The Age* went on to state, is great when it works but when it backfires those who are responsible ought to be brought to account.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Former fast bowler Dennis Lillee was particularly scathing.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Writing in Perth's *The West Australian*, he stated that all who perpetrated this "disaster" must be sacked and Shane Warne be appointed the captain in place of Ponting (because of how Warne had delivered time and time again in the series).
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Losing to other teams is not the end of the world, stated Lillee, but losing the Ashes is.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Former captain Steve Waugh defended the team, calling it "a very good team, a really experienced team.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] They will be disappointed but they will move on from it" he said, but also conceding that the selectors were likely to ponder a few changes given that only three of the Australia team at The Oval were aged under 30.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] "They'll have a couple of players in mind which they will bring in the team over the next couple of years".
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Along with Waugh, selector and former batter David Boon defended their selections.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] "Sometimes you're going to have to make a hard decision to keep a subtle rotation going through so you don't have mass retirements...But you've also got to pick the best cricket team you possibly can to represent your country", he stated.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Ponting was confronted by a large media pack shortly after his arrival at Sydney Airport and said he was not aware of Lillee's comments.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] As long as I am doing the right thing by everyone in my dressing room as the team and the coaching staff, well then that's all I can do...
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] But as long as I am looking after the guys in my dressing room, then I'll be happy," Ponting stated, adding that he wished to remain captain.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Ponting also responded to Lillee's comments that Warne should be captain, and that he made more decisions than Ponting during the series: "I like to talk to a lot of guys out on the field and use their ideas and thoughts.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] I'll go to Gilly [Adam Gilchrist] and even Matty Hayden, Justin Langer, Damien Martyn...
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The way I think is not going to be right 100 percent of the time, but that's the way I do it.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Warne has got a cricket brain as good as anybody around.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Regardless, when the Australian team for the ICC Super Series was announced, three members of the Ashes-losing team were dropped: Damien Martyn was retained only for the ODI squad, while Jason Gillespie and Michael Kasprowicz were dropped altogether.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Brad Hodge, Stuart MacGill and Shane Watson were added in their places.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] While Cricket Australia officials assured that these omissions were not a signal that the Test careers of these three players were over, many experts said otherwise.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] However, all three players made successful returns to the Test team in early 2006.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Lillee once again called for the replacement of Ponting as captain with Warne after the squad announcement, however this was once again rejected.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] With England's victory in the series, the top of the ICC Test Championship rankings ladder changed slightly as the English closed in on the top-ranked Aussies.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] In a BBC interview the week after the series, Simon Jones claimed that the English should one day be regarded as the best, despite statistics and the Test Championship rankings speaking otherwise.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] "The Ashes series was talked about so much.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] People were wondering if England could do it and Glenn McGrath said Australia would win 5–0, but we beat them 2–1 and could have been 3–1 up after Old Trafford," Jones told the BBC.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] "Australia are statistically the best team in the world, and rightly so.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] They've played so much great cricket over the past 10 years and built up an advantage on the points system...
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The team which does well in all three departments will win the series and we have to be very disciplined against England, who have quality batsmen and bowlers." Pakistan later defeated England at home with a 2–0 margin.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Following their performances in the series both Andrew Flintoff and Michael Vaughan were given the Freedom of the City in their home towns of Preston and Sheffield.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] On 29 September, the Royal Mail issued a set of stamps commemorating the Ashes victory.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] The set included two first-class stamps and two worth 68 pence each, the cost of posting a letter to Australia.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] In the 2006 New Year Honours, 11 of the 12 playing members of the England team were awarded the MBE, with captain Vaughan awarded the OBE, for their roles in the successful Ashes victory.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] There was some critical comment that the limited role of some did not warrant the honour.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] However, after the following series in which Australia regained the Ashes in a 5–0 whitewash, the English public began to criticise the celebrations of the previous year.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] This issue also flared up during the Test series when Warne commented on Paul Collingwood's MBE for scoring 17 runs during the 2005 series.
[src:fielding-cricket/2005-ashes-p03] Former England captain Geoffrey Boycott criticised the fact that the MBE had been awarded to the whole team when Warne, who had already taken over 600 wickets by then, had not been honoured.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His strike rate is amongst the highest in the history of both ODI and Test cricket; his 57 ball century against England at Perth in December 2006 is the fourth-fastest century in all Test cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He was the first player to have hit 100 sixes in Test cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His 17 Test centuries and 16 in ODIs are both second only to Sangakkara by a wicket-keeper.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He holds the unique record of scoring at least 50 runs in three consecutive World Cup finals (in 1999, 2003 and 2007).
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His 149 off 101 balls against Sri Lanka in the 2007 World Cup final is rated one of the greatest World Cup innings of all time.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He is one of only three players to have won three World Cup titles.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist was renowned for walking when he considered himself to be out, sometimes contrary to the decision of the umpire.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He made his first-class debut in 1992, his first One-Day International appearance in 1996 in India and his Test debut in 1999.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] During his career, he played for Australia in 96 Test matches and over 270 One-day internationals.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He was Australia's regular vice-captain in both forms of the game, captaining the team when regular captains Steve Waugh and Ricky Ponting were unavailable.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He retired from international cricket in March 2008, though he continued to play domestic tournaments until 2013.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Adam Gilchrist was born in 1971 at Bellingen Hospital, in Bellingen, New South Wales, the youngest of four children.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He and his family lived in Dorrigo, Junee and then Deniliquin where, playing for his school, Deniliquin South Public School, he won the Brian Taber Shield (named after New South Wales cricketer Brian Taber).
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] When Adam was 13, his parents, Stan and June, moved the family to Lismore where he captained the Kadina High School cricket team.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist was selected for the state under-17 team, and in 1989 he was offered a scholarship by London-based Richmond Cricket Club, a scheme he now supports himself.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] During his year at Richmond, he also played junior cricket for Old Actonians Cricket Club's under-17 team, with whom he won the Middlesex League and Cup double.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He moved to Sydney and joined the Gordon District Cricket Club in Sydney Grade Cricket, later moving to Northern Districts.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist is married to his high school sweetheart Melinda (née Sharpe), a dietitian, and they have three sons and a daughter.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His family came under the spotlight in the months leading up to the 2007 Cricket World Cup as one impending birth threatened his presence in the squad; the child was born in February and Gilchrist was able to take part in the tournament.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In 1991, Gilchrist was selected for the Australia Young Cricketers, a national youth team that toured England and played in youth ODIs and Tests.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist scored a century and a fifty in the three Tests.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Upon his return to Australia late in the year, Gilchrist was accepted into the Australian Cricket Academy.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Over the next year, Gilchrist represented the ACA as they played matches against the Second XI of Australia's state teams, and toured South Africa to play provincial youth teams.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In his first season, the team won the Sheffield Shield, Gilchrist scoring an unbeaten 20 in the second innings to secure an easy win over Queensland in the final.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist made 274 runs at an average of 30.44 in his debut season, a score of 75 being his only effort beyond fifty.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He also made his debut in Mercantile Mutual limited overs competition.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He struggled to keep his place in the team, playing only three first-class matches in the following season.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He scored on 43 runs at 8.60; New South Wales won both competitions, but Gilchrist was overlooked for both finals and did not play a single limited overs match.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Due to a lack of opportunities in the dominant New South Wales outfit, Gilchrist joined Western Australia at the start of the 1994–95, where he had to compete with former Test player Tim Zoehrer for the wicket-keeper's berth.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist had no guarantee of selection.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] However, he made a century in a pre-season trial match and seized Zoehrer's place.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The local fans were initially hostile to the move, but Gilchrist won them over.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He made 55 first-class dismissals in his first season, the most by any wicketkeeper in Australian domestic cricket in 1994–95.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] However, he struggled with the bat, scoring 398 runs at 26.53 with seven single figure scores, although he recorded his maiden first-class century in the latter stages of the season, with 126 against South Australia.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist was rewarded with selection in the Young Australia team that toured England in 1995 and played matches against the English counties.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist starred with bat, scoring 490 runs at 70.00 with two centuries.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His second season based in Perth saw him top of the dismissals again, with 58 catches and four stumpings, but, significantly, 835 runs at an impressive batting average of 50.52.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The Warriors made it to the final of the Sheffield Shield, at the Adelaide Oval, where Gilchrist scored 189 not out in the first innings, from only 187 balls, including five sixes.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The innings brought Gilchrist national prominence.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The match ended in a thrilling draw as South Australia's last-wicket pair held on to fend off the visitors.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The hosts thus took the title, having scored more points in the qualifying matches.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist also scored an unbeaten 76 to help Western Australia secure a narrow three-wicket victory over New South Wales in the penultimate limited overs match of the season, which saw them into the final against Queensland, which was lost.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist's form saw him selected for Australia A, a team comprising players close to national selection.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] At the start of the 1996–97 season, sections of the media advocated that he replace Ian Healy as the national wicket-keeper, but Healy struck 161 in the First Test and maintained his position.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist continued to perform strongly on the domestic circuit he topped the dismissals count once again, with 62, along with a batting average of just under 40, although he failed to post a century.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Team success came in the Mercantile Mutual Cup, where the Warriors won by eight wickets against Queensland in the March 1997 final; Gilchrist was not required to bat.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The 1997–98 season ended with Gilchrist top of the dismissals chart for the fourth season in a row with an improved batting average of 47.66, despite playing in only six of the ten qualifying Shield matches due to his becoming a regular member of the national limited overs team.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist registered his maiden–first-class double century with an unbeaten 203 against South Australia early in the season, before returning late in the season after his international commitments were over.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He added 109 against Victoria, and played in the Sheffield Shield final victory over Tasmania, although he scored only eight.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] There was disappointment for the team in the Mercantile Mutual Cup, losing the semi-final to Queensland.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The following season saw Gilchrist's domestic appearances diminish due to his international commitments: he made only a single appearance in the Mercantile Mutual Cup, but still managed to help Western Australia defend the Sheffield Shield, scoring a century in the qualifying rounds.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist's regular selection for Australia meant that he was rarely available for domestic selection after he became the Test wicket-keeper in late-1999; between 1999 and 2005, he made only seven first-class appearances for his state.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He did not play in the 2005–06 Pura Cup and only appeared three times in the limited-overs ING Cup.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist played a total of six seasons in the Indian Premier League (IPL), the major Twenty20 franchise league in India, three for Deccan Chargers and three for Kings XI Punjab.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He was signed by Deccan for the 2008 season, the inaugural season of the competition, having been purchased for US$700,000 in the player auction a few months after his retirement from international cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Before the fourth season of the IPL Gilchrist was bought at the 2011 player auction by Kings XI Punjab for US$900,000 and was, again, appointed as captain, taking over from Kumar Sangakkara who had moved to Deccan.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In March 2012 he was named player-coach of the team for the following season, replacing his friend and former Australia teammate Michael Bevan, whose contract as head coach was not renewed.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] After the team failed to make the play-offs, Gilchrist speculated that he may choose to retire from cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Following the appointment of Darren Lehmann, who had previously worked with Gilchrist at Deccan, as head coach, Gilchrist chose to play one more IPL season for Kings XI, once again as captain.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In May 2013, Gilchrist announced his retirement from the IPL.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] A planned appearance in the first season of the Caribbean Premier League had to be cancelled after an ankle injury and the match proved to be Gilchrist's last in top-class cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In that fixture, Gilchrist took the wicket of Harbhajan Singh, from his one and only ball he ever bowled in a T20 match.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Over his six seasons in the IPL Gilchrist played a total of 82 matches, 48 for Deccan and 34 for Kings XI.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He scored more than 2,000 runs, including two centuries.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He was also the first cricketer to score 1000 runs in IPL.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist signed a short-term contract in November 2009 to play Twenty20 cricket for Middlesex County Cricket Club in England during 2010.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He was appointed interim captain of the T20 team on 11 June following the sudden resignation of Shaun Udal.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He played in seven matches for the team during the 2010 Twenty20 Cup, scoring 212 runs at an average of 30.28, including a century made against Kent at Canterbury, as well as captaining the county against the touring Australians in a one-day match ahead of their ODI series against England.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The season was Gilchrist's only one spent playing county cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist was called up for the Australian One Day International (ODI) team in 1996, his debut coming against South Africa at Faridabad on 25 October 1996 as the 129th Australian ODI cap, after an injury to incumbent Ian Healy.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] While not particularly impressive with the bat on his debut, scoring 18 before being bowled by Allan Donald, Gilchrist took his first catch as an international wicketkeeper, Hansie Cronje departing for a golden duck from the bowling of Paul Reiffel.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He was run out for a duck in his only other ODI on the tour.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Healy resumed his place during the 1996–97 season.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist replaced Healy for the first two ODIs in the 1997 Australian tour of South Africa, after Healy was suspended for dissent.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] When Healy returned Gilchrist maintained his position in the team as a specialist batsman after Mark Waugh sustained a hand injury.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] It was during this series that Gilchrist made his first ODI half-century, with an innings of 77 in Durban.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He totalled 127 runs at 31.75 for the series.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist went on to play in the Texaco Trophy later in 1997 in the 3–0 series loss against England, scoring 53 and 33 in two innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] At the start of the 1997–98 Australian season, Healy and captain Mark Taylor were omitted from the ODI squad as the Australian selectors opted for Gilchrist and Michael di Venuto.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist's elevation was made possible by a change in policy by selectors, who announced that selection for ODI and Test teams would be separate, with Test and ODI specialists selected accordingly, while Healy remained the preferred Test wicket-keeper.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] This came after Australia failed to qualify for the previous season's ODI triangular series final for the first time in 17 years.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The new team was initially unconvincing, losing all four round robin matches against South Africa in the 1997–98 Carlton & United Series, with multiple players filling Taylor's role as Mark Waugh's opening partner without success.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist also struggled batting in the lower order at number seven, the conventional wicket-keeper's batting position, scoring 148 runs at 24.66 in the eight qualifying matches.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In the first final against South Africa at the Melbourne Cricket Ground Gilchrist was selected as Waugh's opening partner.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In a particularly poor start to the new combination, Waugh was run out after a mix-up with Gilchrist.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] However, in the second final, Gilchrist struck his maiden ODI century, spearheading Australia's successful run chase at the Sydney Cricket Ground, securing his position as an opening batsman.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Australia won the third final to claim the title.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Touring New Zealand in February 1998, Gilchrist topped the Australia averages with 200 runs at 50.00, including a match-winning 118 in the first match.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He also effected his first ODI stumping, the wicket of Nathan Astle in the Second ODI in Wellington.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Australia then played two triangular tournaments in Asia.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist struggled in India, scoring 86 runs at 17.20.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He went on to play in the Coca-Cola Cup in Sharjah in April 1998, a triangular tournament between Australia, India and New Zealand.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Australia finished runners-up in the tournament, with Gilchrist taking nine dismissals as wicketkeeper and averaging 37.13 with the bat.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist won a silver medal at the 1998 Commonwealth Games in Kuala Lumpur, the only time men's cricket has been in the Commonwealth Games.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The matches did not have ODI status, and after winning their first four fixtures, Australia lost the final to South Africa, Gilchrist making 15.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He then scored 103 and ended with 190 runs at 63.33 as Australia took a rare 3–0 whitewash on Pakistani soil.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist was in fine form ahead of the 1999 Cricket World Cup with a productive individual performance in the Carlton & United Series in January and February 1999 against Sri Lanka and England.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He finished with 525 runs at a batting average of 43.75 with two centuries—both against Sri Lanka—and a fifty, and a total of 27 dismissals in 12 matches.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His 131 helped Australia set a successful run-chase at the SCG, and he followed this with 154 at the MCG.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The 1999 tour of the West Indies was Australia's last campaign before the World Cup and continued to prove Gilchrist's ability as a wicketkeeper-batsman.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist, with a batting average of 28.71 and a strike rate of nearly 90.00, and seven fielding dismissals in a seven-match series which ended 3–3 with one tie.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist played in every match of Australia's successful World Cup campaign, but struggled at first, with scores of 6, 14 and 0 in the first three matches against Scotland, New Zealand and Pakistan.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Australia lost the latter two matches and had to avoid defeat for six consecutive matches to reach the final.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist's quick-fire 63 runs in 39 balls against Bangladesh helped the Australians into the Super Six stage of the tournament, which was secured with a win over the West Indies, although Gilchrist made only 21.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist continued to struggle in the Super Six phase, scoring 31, 10 and 5 against India, Zimbabwe and South Africa.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Australia won all three matches, the last in the final over, to scrape into the semifinals.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist made only 20 in the semifinal against South Africa, but completed the final act of the match.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] With the scores tied, South Africa were going for the winning run when Gilchrist broke the stumps to complete the run out of Allan Donald; the match was tied, and Australia proceeded to the final as they had won the group stage match against South Africa.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist's 54 in the final helped secure Australia's first world title since 1987 with an eight wicket victory over Pakistan.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] It was a happy ending for Gilchrist, who had struggled through the tournament, with 237 runs at 21.54.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Success at the World Cup was followed by a defeat by Sri Lanka in the final of the Aiwa Cup in August 1999.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist was the most successful batsman and wicket-keeper of the tournament, with 231 runs at 46.20.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] While the Test players battled against Sri Lanka, Gilchrist led Australia A in a limited overs series against India A in Los Angeles.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He then scored 60 runs at 20.00 as the Australians completed a 3–0 whitewash of Zimbabwe in October.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist made his Test match debut in the First Test against Pakistan at the Gabba in Brisbane in November 1999 becoming the 381st Australian Test cricketer.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He replaced Healy, who was dropped after a run of poor form, despite the incumbent's entreaties to the selectors to allow him a farewell game in front of his home crowd.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist's entry into the Test arena coincided with a dramatic rise in Australia's fortunes.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Up to this point, they had played eight Tests in 1999, winning and losing three.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist's icy reception at the Gabba did not faze him; he took five catches, stumped Azhar Mahmood off Shane Warne's bowling and scored a rapid 81, mostly in partnership with ODI partner Waugh, in a match that Australia won comfortably by ten wickets.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In his second Test match he made an unbeaten 149 to help guide Australia to victory in a game that looked well beyond their reach.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Australia were struggling at 5/126 in pursuit of 369 for victory as he joined his Western Australian teammate, Justin Langer, but the pair put on a record-breaking partnership of 238 to seal an Australian win.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist continued his strong run throughout his debut Test season, and ended the summer with 485 runs at 69.28 in six matches, three each against Pakistan and India, adding two fifties against the latter.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist was moderately successful in the following ODIs, the Carlton & United Series; Australia defeated Pakistan 2–0 in a best-of-three final.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist scored 272 runs at 27.20; his best effort was 92 in a 152-run victory over India on Australia Day.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist then scored 251 runs at 41.66 in the ODIs during a tour of New Zealand.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The highlight was a 128 in Christchurch that propelled Australia to a score of 6/349.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist was named man of the match in two of the games.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In the Third Test against New Zealand in 2000, Gilchrist recorded the third best Test performance ever by a wicketkeeper, and the best by an Australian, taking ten catches in the match.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Although Gilchrist's batting was modest, yielding 144 runs at 36.00, Australia took a 3–0 clean sweep.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In two home and away ODI series against South Africa, Gilchrist had a quiet time, scoring 170 runs at 26.66.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] South Africa won three of the six matches, with one tie.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Later that year, he was handed the vice-captaincy of the Australian team in place of Shane Warne, who had been plagued by a number of off-field controversies, including an altercation with some teenage boys, and a sex scandal with a British nurse.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The 2000–01 season saw a West Indian touring party and Gilchrist warmed up with consecutive first-class centuries for Western Australia.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Captaining his Test team for the first time in place of the injured Steve Waugh in the Third Test in Adelaide.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist scored only 9 and 10 not out, but a ten-wicket haul from Colin Miller resulted in a hard-fought five-wicket victory for Australia.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist described the match as "the proudest moment of my career".
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Waugh resumed the captaincy on his return to the team for the Fourth and Fifth Tests, with the series finishing in a 5–0 whitewash.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist scored 241 runs at 48.20 with two fifties.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In the ensuing ODI tournament, Gilchrist scored 326 runs at 36.22 with a top-score of 98 as the Australians won all ten matches.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Up to this point, Gilchrist had played in 14 Tests, all in Australasia, and all of which had been won.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Australia's run of 15 consecutive Test wins faced a steep challenge on the tour of India, where they had not won a Test series since 1969–70.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Australia's streak looked in danger during the First Test in Mumbai when they fell to 5/99 in reply to India's 171 when Gilchrist came to the crease.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He counterattacked savagely, scoring 122 in just 112 balls, and featuring in a 197-run partnership with Matthew Hayden in only 32 overs.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] This swung the momentum back to Australia, who reached 349.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist took six catches and was named Man of the Match in a ten wicket victory, extending the world record run to 16.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist's form dipped momentarily, with a rare *king pair* (two golden ducks in the same match) in the Second Test in Kolkata and just two runs in his two innings in Chennai.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He was out LBW four consecutive times in the last two Tests, three of these to Harbhajan Singh, who took 32 wickets in the series to end Australia's run by inflicting a 2–1 series loss.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His one-day form remained strong, with 172 runs at 43.00 in the ODI series in India, as Australia bounced back to win the series 3–2.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] During this series he captained the ODI team for the first time, winning all three of the matches under his captaincy.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist played a pivotal role in the 2001 Ashes series which Australia won 4–1, with 340 runs at a batting average of 68.00 and 26 dismissals in the five-match series.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist warmed up by putting his ODI struggles on English soil in 1999 behind him, scoring 248 runs at 49.60 in the triangular tournament preceding the Tests, scoring an unbeaten 76 in the final win over Pakistan.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist put the disappointment of India behind him in the First Test at Edgbaston, scoring 152 from only 143 balls.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The allowed Australia to reach 576 in only 545 minutes, and set up an innings victory that set the tone for the series.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist then added 90 in the eight-wicket win in the Second Test at Lord's, before turning the tide in the Third Test at Trent Bridge.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Australia slumped to 7/105 in reply to the hosts' 185, but Gilchrist's 54 took the tourists to 190 before a seven-wicket win resulted in the retention of the Ashes.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist captained the team in the Fourth Test at Headingley after an injury to Steve Waugh.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] After persistent rain interruptions, Gilchrist declared with Australia four down at tea on the fourth day, leaving England with a target of 315, which, despite losing two early wickets, they reached with six wickets to spare, (Mark Butcher scoring an unbeaten 173, including 24 boundaries).
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist failed to pass 25 in the last two Tests, but it had been a productive season; he scored centuries in both of Australia's county matches.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Two home series followed in the 2001–02 season, a fully drawn (0–0) three match series against New Zealand and a whitewash over South Africa 3–0.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist scored 118 in the First Test against New Zealand and an unbeaten 83 in the Third Test in Perth as the Australians held on for a draw with three wickets intact.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] However, Gilchrist did little in the triumph over South Africa, failing to pass 35.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He ended the summer Tests with 353 runs at 50.42.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In the ensuing ODIs, Gilchrist scored only 97 runs at 16.16.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The Australian selectors sought to accommodate Hayden, who had been successful as a Test opener, into the ODI team by rotating him with Gilchrist and Waugh, but this appeared to unsettle the team.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] With a newly fragile top order, Australia failed to qualify for the finals, and the Waugh brothers were dropped from the team, ending Gilchrist's four-year partnership with Mark.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Ricky Ponting was promoted to the captaincy ahead of vice captain Gilchrist.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The Australians then toured South Africa the next month and it was during the First Test in Johannesburg that Gilchrist broke the record for the fastest double century in Tests on 23 February, requiring 212 balls for the feat.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] This was eight balls quicker than Ian Botham's innings against India at The Oval in 1982.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He ended unbeaten on 204, having featured in a partnership of 317 with Damien Martyn at a run rate of 5.5.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] South Africa were demoralised and lost by an innings after being forced to follow on.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The record lasted only one month, however, with New Zealand's Nathan Astle taking 59 balls less to reach the milestone during an innings in March 2002.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In the Second Test at Cape Town, Gilchrist struck 138 from 108 balls to set up a first innings lead and eventual four-wicket win.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He then top-scored with 91 in the Third Test, and although Australia lost the match, Gilchrist ended the series with an astonishing 473 at 157.66 from just 474 balls, in addition to 14 dismissals.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist captained the ODI team, once again for a single match, against Kenya in Nairobi during the PSO Tri-Nation Tournament.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Despite Australia's unbeaten run in the competition, the final, against Pakistan was abandoned due to rain, so the teams shared the trophy.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] During the six middle months of 2002, Gilchrist played in 18 ODIs, scoring 562 runs at 31.22, including a century, recovering from his slump.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] After scoring fifties in the first two Tests, Gilchrist scored a counter-attacking 133 from 121 balls in the Fifth Test at the SCG, but was unable to prevent Australia's only loss of the series.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] From the time of his debut up to the 2003 World Cup, Gilchrist's played in 40 Tests in series.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] With the exception of the 2001 tour of India, when he averaged 24.80 (he made 124 runs in the series; 122 of them came in one innings), his performances with the bat were such that he was described at the time as the "finest batsman-wicketkeeper to have graced the game".
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] At one point in March 2002, Gilchrist's Test average was over 60; the second-highest for any established player in Test history, and he topped the ICC Test batting rankings in May 2002.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist warmed up for the World Cup in South Africa by scoring 310 runs at 44.28 in the triangular tournament in Australia against England and Sri Lanka.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His performances over the past year were recognised with the Allan Border Medal.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist played in all but one of the matches in Australia's successful defence of their World Cup title; he was rested for the group match against the Netherlands.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He finished the tournament with 408 runs at an average of 40.80 at a strike rate of 105.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He scored four half-centuries, and was run out against Sri Lanka in the Super Six stage just a single run short of a century.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In the semi-final, he scored 22 before being caught off an inside-edge onto pad off the bowling of Aravinda de Silva.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The umpire gave no reaction, however Gilchrist walked off the pitch after a moment's pause.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In the final, India elected to field first and Gilchrist hammered 57 from 48 balls, featuring in a century opening stand with Hayden to seize the initiative.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] This laid the foundation for Australia's 2/359 and a crushing 125-run win, ending an unbeaten campaign.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist was also the competition's most successful wicketkeeper, making 21 dismissals.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Success in the World Cup was followed up by a tour of the West Indies where Gilchrist was part of a team that won both the ODI and Test series.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He scored 282 runs at 70.50 with one century in the four Tests, and 212 runs at 35.33 in the ODIs.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The Australians then defeated a touring Bangladeshi cricket team in short series in both forms of the game.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist was only sporadically required with the bat.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] However, he returned to form in the Second Test Kandy, scoring a quickfire 144 in the second innings to set up a 27-run win after Australia conceded a 91-run first innings lead.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] However, he maintained high standards in ODIs during this period, including 111 against India in Bangalore, 172 against Zimbabwe, just one run short of Mark Waugh's Australian record, and two further half-centuries in the VB Series in Australia.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His success in One-day cricket was underlined by his rise to the top of the ICC ODI batting rankings in February 2004.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] However, he was unable to maintain this form on the 2004 tours of Sri Lanka, Zimbabwe and the Champions Trophy in England, accumulating 253 runs at 28.11 in 11 innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist then scored 115 runs at 28.75 in two Tests at home to Sri Lanka in mid-2004, and captained in the First Test win in Darwin with Ponting absent.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He took the captaincy of the Test team once again, in place of the injured Ricky Ponting, and led the Australian team to a historic 2–1 series victory in India, a feat last achieved in 1969.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Ponting recovered to lead the team in the Fourth Test, Australia's only loss.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist returned to form when New Zealand toured Australia at the start of southern hemisphere season.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He scored 126 and 50 in the 2–0 Test series clean sweep and scored fifties in both ODIs.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He then scored 230 runs at 76.66 in three Tests against Pakistan, including a rapid 113 in the Third Test at the SCG as Australia won all five Tests during the summer.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He made it three successive Test centuries with 121 and 162 in the first two Tests on the tour of New Zealand, before ending with an unbeaten 60 in the Third Test; he totalled 343 runs at 114.33 for the series.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His ODI form in the early part of 2005 remained moderate, with 308 runs at 28.00 during the southern summer.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist was in strong form ahead of the Tests, scoring 393 runs at 49.13 in the ODIs in England.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The highlight was the 121 not out in the final game of the one-day NatWest Series, Gilchrist being awarded the man-of-the-match award.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] However, he performed poorly in the five Tests, with 204 runs at 25.50.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Just as in India in 2001, Australia lost 2–1.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Australia and Gilchrist returned to form after the Ashes in the series against the ICC World XI.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist scored 45, 103 and 32 as Australia swept the ODIs 3–0, and top-scored with 94 in the first innings of the one-off Test, which Australia won.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] However, this did not transfer into the regular international matches.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In six home Tests against the West Indies and South Africa in 2005–06, Gilchrist managed only 190 runs at 23.75, but Australia was unhindered, winning 3–0 and 2–0 respectively.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His one-day form also began to suffer, scoring only 11 runs in three ODIs in New Zealand and 13 in the first two matches of the VB Series.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He was rested for two games and returned to form against Sri Lanka on 29 January 2006 on his home ground, the WACA, hitting 116 runs off 105 balls to lead Australia to victory.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He continued in this vein with the fastest ever century by an Australian in just 67 balls against Sri Lanka at the Gabba, ending with 122 as Australia won the deciding third final by nine wickets.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] After a slow start, he ended the series with 432 runs at 48.00.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The purple patch ended on the tour of South Africa and then Bangladesh.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He scored 206 runs at 29.42 in five Tests and 248 runs at 35.42 in eight ODIs, inflated by a 144 in the First Test against Bangladesh.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Despite this, Australia won all five Tests.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist scored 130 runs at 26.00, including a 92 against the West Indies as Australia won the 2006 Champions Trophy in India.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] On 16 December 2006, during the Third Ashes Test at the WACA, Gilchrist scored a century in 57 balls, including twelve fours and four sixes, which at the time was the second fastest recorded Test century.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] At 97 runs from 54 balls, Gilchrist needed three runs from the next delivery to better Viv Richards' record set in 1986.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The ball delivered by Matthew Hoggard was wide and Gilchrist was unable to score from it.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He later claimed that the "batting pyrotechnics" had been the result of a miscommunication between Michael Clarke and him with the Australian captain Ricky Ponting; Gilchrist had actually been told *not* to score quick runs with a view to declaring the innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He ended the 2006–07 Ashes with a century and two fifties, totalling 229 runs at 45.80 at a strike rate of over 100 as Australia regained the Ashes with a 5–0 whitewash.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] It was an inconsistent series; aside from three scores mentioned, Gilchrist failed to pass one in his other three innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Between Ashes series, Gilchrist had averaged only 25 with one Test century.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] However, both he and Australia suffered a surprising string of poor results in the 2006–07 Commonwealth Bank Series, Gilchrist managing an average of only 22.20 during the tournament.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Australia won seven of their eight qualifying matches, but England won with two finals victories over the Australians.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist scored 60 and 61 in the first two matches but did not pass 30 thereafter.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He was then rested for Australia's winless three-match ODI tour of New Zealand, before his selection for the 2007 Cricket World Cup.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Having previously indicated that it was highly likely that he would retire after the 2007 World Cup, he then stated a desire to play on afterwards.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist and Australia started their 2007 World Cup campaign by winning all three of their matches in Group A, against Scotland, the Netherlands and South Africa.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Australia won all seven of their matches in the Super8 stage with little difficulty—the margins of victory exceeded 80 runs or six wickets in every instance.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] They topped the table and thus qualifying for a semi-final rematch against fourth-placed South Africa.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist opened the Australian batting in each match, taking a pinch-hitting role in the opening powerplays.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Initially successful in the group matches, scoring 46, 57 and 42, he failed in the first Super8 match against West Indies (7), but bounced back to score a second half-century (59 not out) in a ten-wicket victory against Bangladesh in a match drastically shortened due to rain.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] After a run of middling scores, he failed again in the final Super8 match against New Zealand.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] As a batsman, Gilchrist was dismissed for a single run in the semi-final against South Africa, despite which Australia won by seven wickets.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist opened the batting against Sri Lanka in the final.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] This was Gilchrist's third successive World Cup final, and the third time he scored at least 50 runs in a World Cup final and he went on to make his only ever century in a world cup match (his previous best World Cup score having been 99 against Sri Lanka in the 2003 tournament).
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist went on to score 149 runs off 104 balls with thirteen fours and eight sixes, the highest individual score in a World Cup final, eclipsing his captain Ricky Ponting's score of 140 in the 2003 final.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Australia won and he was named the man of the match.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Subsequently there has been some controversy over Gilchrist's use of a squash ball inside his glove during this innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The MCC stated that Gilchrist had not acted against the laws or the spirit of the game, since there is no restriction against the external or internal form of batting gloves.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In September 2007, Gilchrist played in the inaugural World Twenty20.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He scored 169 runs at 33.80 as Australia were knocked out by India in the semifinals.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist then scored 208 runs at 34.66 as Australia took an away ODI series against India 4–2.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In November, Gilchrist's peers voted him the greatest Australian ODI cricketer ever, for which he was awarded an honour at an ACA function before Australia's second Test against Sri Lanka.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He was only required to bat once in the Tests, and made 67 not out as Australia swept Sri Lanka aside 2–0.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] On 26 January 2008 during the 4th and final Test of the 2007–08 series against India, Gilchrist announced that he would retire from international cricket at the end of the season.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] A back injury kept Ricky Ponting off the field for sections of the Indian's second innings, resulting in Gilchrist captaining the team for part of the final two days of his Test cricket career.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] India batted out the match for a draw, so Gilchrist's 14 in the first innings was his final Test innings; he took his 379th and final catch when Virender Sehwag was caught behind.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist had scored only 150 runs at 21.42 in his final Test series.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist managed only seven and two in the finals.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His highlight of the series was his scoring 118 and being named Man of the Match in his final match at his adopted home in Perth on 15 February 2008, against Sri Lanka.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He ended his final series with 322 runs at 32.20.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist's attacking batting was a key part of Australia's one-day success, as he usually opened the batting.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He was a part of the successful 1999, 2003 and 2007 Cricket World Cup campaigns.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist's Test batting average in the upper 40s is unusually high for a wicket-keeper.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He retired from Test cricket at 45th on the all–time list of highest batting averages.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] At the end of his Test career he had established a Test strike-rate of 82 runs per hundred balls, at the time the third highest since balls were recorded in full.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His combination of attack and consistency create one of the most dynamic world cricketers ever, playing shots to all areas of the field with uncommon timing.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He was second on the all-time list of most sixes in Tests at 100 with only Brendon McCullum ahead of him with 107.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist's skills as a wicket-keeper were sometimes questioned; some claimed that he was the best keeper in Australia whilst others that Victorian wicket-keeper Darren Berry was the best Australian wicket-keeper of the 1990s and early 2000s.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist attributed his batting techniques from early training with his father, where he would defend shots, sometimes only gripping the bat with his top (right) hand, and would end a session to simply play attacking shots with tennis balls to end on a positive and fun note.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He also adopted a naturally high grip where both hands were closer to the end of the handle for more top hand control.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist successfully kept wicket for fast bowlers Glenn McGrath and Brett Lee for most of his international career.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] His partnerships with McGrath and Lee are second and fourth respectively in both test and ODI history for the number of wickets taken.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] With Alec Stewart and Mark Boucher, he shares the record for most catches (6) by a wicketkeeper in a ODI match, having achieved this feat five times.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In 2007 he took six dismissals and scored a half century in the same ODI for the second time; he remains the only player to do so even once.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] This record was surpassed seven years later by Kumar Sangakkara.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] It is unusual for professional batsmen to "walk"; that is, to agree that they have been dismissed and leave the field of play without waiting for (or contrary to) an umpire's decision.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist reignited this debate by walking during a high-profile match, the 2003 World Cup semi-final against Sri Lanka, after the umpire ruled him to be not out.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He has since proclaimed himself to be "a walker", or a batsman who will consistently walk, and has done so on numerous occasions.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] On one occasion against Bangladesh, Gilchrist walked but TV replays failed to suggest any contact between his bat and the ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Without such contact, he could not have been caught out.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Ricky Ponting has declared on several occasions that he is not a walker but will leave it to each player to decide whether they wish to walk or not.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] While no other Australian top-order batsmen have expressly declared themselves to be walkers, lower-order batsmen Jason Gillespie and Michael Kasprowicz both walked during Test matches in India in 2004.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In 2004, New Zealand captain Stephen Fleming accused Gilchrist of conducting a "walking crusade" when Craig McMillan refused to walk after Gilchrist had caught him off an edge from the bowling of Jason Gillespie in the First Test in Brisbane.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] After the appeal was turned down by the umpire, who did not hear the edge, Gilchrist goaded McMillan about the edge, and McMillan's angry response was picked up by the stump microphone: "...not everyone is walking, Gilly ... not everyone has to walk, mate...".
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] The taunt was arguably effective, however, as McMillan, perhaps distracted, missed the next ball and was given out leg before wicket.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist said in his autobiography that he had "zero support in the team" for his stance and that he felt that the topic made the dressing room uncomfortable.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] He added that he "felt isolated" and "silently accused of betraying the team.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist has been noted for his emotional outbursts on the cricket field, and has been fined multiple times for dissent against umpiring decisions.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In January 2006, he was fined 40% of his match fee in an ODI against South Africa.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] In another instance, in early 2004 in Sri Lanka, Gilchrist audibly argued with umpire Peter Manuel after batting partner Andrew Symonds was given out.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] After the argument concluded, Manuel consulted umpiring partner Billy Bowden and reversed his decision, recalling Symonds to the crease.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Gilchrist was also reprimanded by the Australian Cricket Board for publicly questioning the legality of Muttiah Muralitharan's bowling action in 2002, as his comments were found to be in breach of the clause in the player code of conduct relating to "detrimental public comment".
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] During the 2003 World Cup, Gilchrist accused Pakistani wicket-keeper Rashid Latif of making a racist remark towards him while the latter was batting in their group match.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p01] Latif who was cleared by match referee Clive Lloyd, threatened to sue Gilchrist for this claim.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] Gilchrist was one of five Wisden Cricketers of the Year for 2002, and Australia's One-day International Player of the Year in 2003 and 2004.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] He was awarded the Allan Border Medal in 2003, and was the only Australian cricketer who was a current player at the time to have been named in "Richie Benaud's Greatest XI" in 2004.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] A panel of prominent cricket writers selected him in Australia's all-time best XI for ESPNcricinfo.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] In 2010, Gilchrist was made a Member of the Order of Australia (AM) for his services to cricket and the community.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] He was inducted into the Sport Australia Hall of Fame in 2012.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] On 9-December-2013, ICC announced that they had inducted Gilchrist in the prestigious ICC Hall of Fame.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] He was named an Australia Post Legend of Cricket in 2021.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] Gilchrist's autobiography *True Colours*, published in 2008, was the subject of much controversy.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] Gilchrist questioned the integrity of leading Indian batsman Sachin Tendulkar in relation to the evidence he presented in the Monkeygate dispute, which was about allegations of racism against Harbhajan Singh.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] The autobiography said that Tendulkar told the first hearing that he could not hear what Harbhajan said to Andrew Symonds; Gilchrist said that he was "certain he *"Tendulkar*" was telling the truth" because he was "a fair way away".
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] Gilchrist then questioned why Tendulkar then agreed with Harbhajan's claim at the second hearing that the exchange was an obscenity, and concluded that the process was "a joke".
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] He also raised questions over Tendulkar's sportsmanship and said he was "hard to find for a changing-room handshake after we have beaten India".
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] There was a backlash in India, which forced Gilchrist to clarify his position.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] Gilchrist later insisted that he did not accuse Tendulkar of lying in his testimony.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] He also denied calling the Indian a "bad sport" in regards to the handshake issue.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] Tendulkar responded by saying that "those remarks came from someone who doesn't know me enough.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] The law change was described as "a load of horse crap.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] That's rubbish." Gilchrist claimed that Muralitharan threw the ball and alleged that the ICC protected him because Sri Lankan cricket authorities portrayed any criticism of the bowler's legitimacy as racism and a witch-hunt conducted by whites.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] In response to these comments, former Sri Lankan captain Marvan Atapattu said that by questioning the credentials of players like Muralitharan and Tendulkar, Gilchrist had done no good to his own reputation.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] Outside cricket, Gilchrist is an ambassador for the charity World Vision in India, a country in which he is popular due to his cricketing achievements, and sponsors a boy whose father has died.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] He was approached in early 2005 by the US baseball franchise, the Boston Red Sox, with a view to him playing for them when his cricket career ended.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] However, he was selected for the 2007 Cricket World Cup and announced his retirement from Test and One-Day cricket in early 2008.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] In March 2008, Gilchrist joined the Nine Network.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] Gilchrist has appeared as one of a panel of revolving co-hosts for the revived *Wide World of Sports Weekend Edition*.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] He made his debut on the program in March 2008, and commentates on Fox Sport's cricket coverage during the Australian summer.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] In 2013 Gilchrist joined Ricky Ponting and various other names in cricket to commentate for Channel Ten in the third series of the Big Bash League.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] As Amway Australia Ambassador, Gilchrist has played a role in many of their charity events.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] In August 2010, he presented the Freedom Wheels program, an initiative to provide modified bikes to kids with disabilities, a cheque for $20,000.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] Gilchrist was the chair of the National Australia Day Council from 2008 to 2014.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] In 2008, Gilchrist supported debate on whether Australia Day should be moved to a new date because the current date marks British settlement of New South Wales and is offensive to many Aboriginal Australians.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] Gilchrist has had a number of company directorships outside of cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] His appointment to the board of ASX listed sandalwood company TFS Corporation, committee member of Commonwealth Business Forum in Perth and director of Travelex.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] In October 2025, Gilchist launched 'El Arquero' Tequila, created by Destiladora de Los Altos distillery , a 3rd Generation family-owned business.
[src:fielding-cricket/adam-gilchrist-p02] Gilchrist also plays himself on the Australian comedy series *How to Stay Married*.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] The younger son of former English Test cricketer Micky Stewart, Stewart was educated at Clarence Avenue Infants' School, Coombe Hill Junior School and Tiffin School in Kingston upon Thames.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] He made his debut for Surrey in 1981, earning a reputation as an aggressive opening batsman and occasional wicketkeeper.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] Stewart is a well-known supporter of Surrey County Cricket Club and Chelsea Football Club.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] When shirt numbers were introduced for One Day International cricket, Stewart chose the number 4 shirt in honour of his favourite Chelsea player when growing up, John Hollins, and kept that shirt number throughout his career.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] Stewart made his England debut in the first Test of the 1989/90 tour of the West Indies, along with Nasser Hussain, who would eventually replace him as England captain.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] At the start of his career, Stewart was a specialist opening batsman for England, with wicketkeeping duties being retained by Jack Russell, who was generally recognised as the superior gloveman and who batted down the order.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] However, Russell, the inferior batsman, would often be dropped to improve the balance of the side (i.e. to accommodate an extra bowler or batsman), in which case Stewart would don the gloves.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] After enduring years of selection and deselection, Russell retired from international cricket in 1998, leaving Stewart unrivalled as England's keeper-batsman until his own retirement in 2003.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] His highest Test score, 190, was against Pakistan in the drawn first Edgbaston Test on 4 June 1992; it was his fourth century in five Tests.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] In 1994 at the Kensington Oval he became only the seventh Englishman to score centuries in both innings of a Test match, scoring 118 and 143 as the West Indies were beaten at their Bridgetown "fortress" for the first time since 1935.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] Stewart's batting average (39.54) is the lowest of any player to have scored 8000 or more runs in Test cricket: he is the only player to have scored over 8000 runs despite an average of under 40.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] However, when played as a specialist batsman in Test cricket, Stewart averaged 46.90 in 51 games with 9 centuries.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] Since World War II, only Len Hutton, Geoff Boycott, Dennis Amiss and Alastair Cook have bettered Stewart's average of 46 as a specialist opening batsman for England.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] As wicketkeeper-batsman he averaged 34.92 from 82 tests, higher than many of his contemporaries.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] He was on the losing side in a record 54 Test Matches.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] Stewart holds the record for scoring the most test runs without a career double century in test history (8463).
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] Stewart was groomed for the England captaincy under Graham Gooch, deputising for him in four tests in India and Sri Lanka in 1993, but when Gooch retired from the captaincy later that year Mike Atherton was chosen to succeed him.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] Stewart was asked to captain England in 1998 when Mike Atherton resigned.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] Despite being aged 35 at the time, Stewart's level of fitness was impeccable, especially bearing in mind that most players do not continue beyond 37.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] As it was Stewart went on to play for England beyond his 40th birthday – but as events were to transpire, his captaincy of England barely lasted 12 months.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] In his first series as captain, against South Africa, Stewart scored an outstanding 164 in the third Test at Old Trafford to salvage a draw, a result which eventually enabled England to overturn a 1–0 deficit to win the series 2–1.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] Nonetheless, failures against Australia and in the 1999 Cricket World Cup saw him sacked from the captaincy to be replaced by Hussain.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] During his captaincy, he dropped down the order and did not open the batting.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] He continued to deputise occasionally as captain of England's one-day side, and became the second international captain to concede a match in 2001, after a pitch invasion during a One Day International against Pakistan rendered the continuation of play impossible.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] He continued as an England player for five more seasons, and became only the fourth player to score a century in his 100th Test, scoring 105 against the West Indies at Old Trafford in 2000.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] Stewart also set a record for playing the most number of ODI matches(28) as a captain who has kept wicket and opened the batting.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] In 2004, Stewart became a founding director of Arundel Promotions with specific responsibility for player management and representation.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] Cricket playing clients include Paul Collingwood, Ian Bell, Ashley Giles and Matt Prior.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] In 2009, Stewart rejoined Surrey as a part-time consultant to the coaching staff specialising in batting, wicket keeping and mentoring.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] Since retiring from playing Stewart has taken on the role as the Club Ambassador for Surrey County Cricket Club and was made an executive director in 2011.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] On 17 June 2013, it was announced by Surrey County Cricket Club that Stewart would take charge of first team affairs following the sacking of Chris Adams, until a long term successor was found.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] In October 2013 the club announced that Graham Ford would become head coach in February 2014, with Stewart becoming Director of Cricket, a new position.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] In March 2024, he announced that he would be stepping down from this role at the end of the year.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] In October 2024 it was announced that Stewart would remain at the club as a part-time high-performance cricket advisor.
[src:fielding-cricket/alec-stewart] He was the subject of *This Is Your Life* in 2003 when he was surprised by Michael Aspel while playing golf at the Royal Automobile Club in Epsom.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] An **all-rounder** is a cricketer who regularly performs well at both batting and bowling.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Although all bowlers must bat and quite a handful of batsmen do bowl occasionally, most players are skilled in only one of the two disciplines and are considered specialists.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Some wicket-keepers have the skills of a specialist batter and have been referred to as all-rounders, but the term *wicket-keeper-batter* is more commonly applied to them, even if they are substitute wicket keepers who also bowl.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] There is no precise qualification for a player to be considered an all-rounder and use of the term tends to be subjective.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] The generally accepted criterion is that a "genuine allrounder" is someone whose batting or bowling skills, considered alone, would be good enough to win them a place in the team.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Another definition of a "genuine all-rounder" is a player who can, through both batting and bowling (though not necessarily both in the same match), consistently "win matches for the team" (i.e., propel their team to victory by an outstanding individual performance).
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] By either definition, a genuine all-rounder is quite rare and extremely valuable to a team, effectively operating as two players.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Confusion sometimes arises when a specialist bowler performs well with the bat.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] For example, West Indies pace bowler Malcolm Marshall achieved ten scores of 50 or above in 107 Test innings between 1978 and 1991, but had a batting average of less than 19.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] He would be termed a "useful lower-order batsman", or indeed "a bowler who bats a bit".
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] One of the main constraints to becoming a recognised all-rounder is that batters and bowlers "peak" at different ages.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Batters tend to reach their peak in their late twenties after their technique has matured through experience.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Conversely, fast bowlers often peak in their early to mid-twenties at the height of their physical prowess.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Other bowlers, mostly spinners but also fast bowlers who can "swing" the ball, are still effective in their later careers.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] In 2013, Ali Bacher used statistical analysis to argue that there had only been 42 genuine all-rounders in the history of Test cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] He rated Garry Sobers as the best, followed by Jacques Kallis.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] One commonly used statistical rule of thumb is that a player's batting average (the higher the better) should be greater than their bowling average (the lower the better).
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] In Test cricket, only two players i.e., Garfield Sobers and Jacques Kallis, have batting averages that are 20 greater than their bowling averages over their entire careers.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] However, some other players have achieved such a differential over significant parts of their careers, such as Imran Khan who across 54 Test matches during the 1980s averaged 44 with the bat and 19 with the ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Wally Hammond and Doug Walters managed differences of 20.7 and 19.2, respectively, between their batting and bowling averages, however, they were generally regarded as occasional bowlers who could break partnerships rather than genuine all-rounders.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] In overall first-class cricket, there are several players with significantly higher batting averages.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Statistically, few can challenge Frank Woolley who had a batting average of 40.77 and a bowling average of 19.87.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Woolley took over 2000 wickets in his career, scored more runs than anyone except Jack Hobbs and is the only non-wicketkeeper to have taken more than 1000 catches.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Many all-rounders are better at bowling than batting or *vice versa*.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Very few are equally good at both and hardly any have been outstanding at both.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Thus the terms "bowling all-rounder" and "batting all-rounder" have come into use.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] For example, Richard Hadlee had an excellent bowling average of 22.29 in Tests and a passable (yet unspectacular) batting average of 27.16, leading him to be termed a "bowling all-rounder", while the same can be said about Jason Holder, Kyle Mayers, Justin Greaves and Chris Woakes.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Meanwhile, a player like Jacques Kallis (batting average of 55.37 and bowling average of 32.65 in Tests) is known as a "batting all-rounder".
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Also, batting all-rounders may not bowl much due to injury concerns (e.g.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Corey Anderson, Angelo Mathews), or their batting skills are far better than their bowling to begin with (e.g.
[src:fielding-cricket/all-rounder] Kane Williamson, Steve Smith) to the point they revert to being known as a batsman.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] In cricket, **batting** is the act or skill of hitting the ball with a bat to score runs and prevent the loss of one's wicket.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Any player who is currently batting is, since September 2021, officially referred to as a **batter** regardless of whether batting is their particular area of expertise.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Historically, *batsman* and *batswoman* were used, and these terms remain in widespread use.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Batters have to adapt to various conditions when playing on different cricket pitches, especially in different countries; therefore, as well as having outstanding physical batting skills, top-level batters will have quick reflexes, excellent decision-making skills, and be good strategists.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] During an innings two members of the batting side are on the pitch at any time: the one facing the current delivery from the bowler is called the *striker*, while the other is the *non-striker*.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] When a batter is out, they are replaced by a teammate.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] This continues until the end of the innings, which in most cases is when 10 of the team members are out, whereupon the other team gets a turn to bat.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Batting tactics and strategy vary depending on the type of match being played as well as the current state of play.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The main concerns for the batters are not to lose their wicket and to score as many runs as quickly as possible.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] These objectives generally conflict—to score quickly, risky shots must be played, increasing the chance that the batter will be dismissed, while the batter's safest choice with a careful wicket-guarding stroke may be not to attempt any runs at all.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Depending on the situation, batters may abandon attempts at run-scoring in an effort to preserve their wicket, or may attempt to score runs as quickly as possible with scant concern for the possibility of being dismissed.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Unlike various other bat-and-ball sports, cricket batters may hit the ball in any direction to score runs, and can use creative shots to do so.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] As with all other cricket statistics, batting statistics and records are given much attention and provide a measure of a player's effectiveness.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The main statistic for batting is a player's batting average.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] This is calculated by dividing the number of runs they have scored by the number of times they have been dismissed (not by the number of innings they have played).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Any player, regardless of their area of special skill, is referred to as a "batter" (historically as a "batsman" or "batswoman") while they are batting.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The batter's act of hitting the ball is called a "shot" or "stroke".
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A player who is selected for the team mainly for their batting skill is often referred to as simply a batter, regardless of whether they are currently batting, or sometimes as a specialist batter.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A specialist bowler or wicket-keeper, on the other hand, would only be referred to as a batter when they are actually batting.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] In 2021, the Laws of Cricket were amended to officially use the term "batter" for gender neutrality, and this is increasingly the preferred term in some media outlets.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A standard batting technique has been developed which is used by most batters.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Technique refers to the batter's stance before the ball is bowled as well as the movement of the hands, feet, head, and body in the execution of a cricket stroke.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The movement of the batter for a particular delivery depends on the shot being attempted.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Front-foot shots are played with the weight on the front foot (left foot for a right-hander) and are usually played when the ball is pitched up to the batter, while back-foot shots are played putting the weight onto the back foot, usually to bowling that is pitched short.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Shots may also be referred to as vertical or straight-bat shots, in which the bat is swung vertically at the ball (e.g. when playing a drive or leg glance), or horizontal or cross-bat shots, in which the bat is swung horizontally at the ball (e.g. when playing the pull or cut shot).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] While a batter is not limited in where or how they may hit the ball, the development of good technique has gone hand in hand with the development of a standard or orthodox cricket shots played to specific types of deliveries.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] These "textbook" shots are standard material found in many coaching manuals.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The advent of limited overs cricket, with its emphasis on rapid run-scoring, has led to increasing use of unorthodox shots to hit the ball into gaps where there are no fielders.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Unorthodox shots are typically—but not always—more high-risk than orthodox shots due to some aspects of good batting technique being abandoned.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The stance is the position in which a batter stands to have the ball bowled to them.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] An ideal stance is "comfortable, relaxed and balanced", with the feet 40 centimetres (16 in) apart, parallel and astride the crease.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Additionally, the front shoulder should be pointing down the wicket, the head facing the bowler, the weight equally balanced and the bat near the back toe.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A slight crouch is adopted in order to be in a more effective striking posture whilst also isometrically loading the muscles; this allows the stroke to be played more dynamically.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] As the ball is about to be released, the batter will lift their bat up behind in anticipation of playing a stroke and will shift their weight onto the balls of their feet.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] By doing this they are ready to move swiftly into position to address the ball once they see its path out of the bowler's hand.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Although the textbook, side-on stance is the most common, a few international players, such as Shivnarine Chanderpaul and Steve Smith, use an "open" or "square on" stance.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Backlift is how a batter lifts their bat in preparation for hitting the ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] While the bat should be raised as vertically as possible, coaching manuals often suggest that correct technique is for the bat to be slightly angled from the perpendicular; a common instruction is to point the face of the bat in the direction of first or second slip.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Some players (notably, in recent times, Brian Lara, Virender Sehwag) have employed an exaggerated backlift.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Others, who have employed the more unorthodox open stance, such as Peter Willey, had a more abbreviated backlift.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Depending upon the path of the ball, the batter will either move forward or back in their attempt to intercept it.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A forward movement is designated a *front foot shot*, whereas a backward movement is designated a *back foot shot*.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A front foot shot is typically used to address a ball arriving at between ankle and thigh height.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The batter will step forward towards the ball, bending their front knee to bring the bat down to the anticipated height of the ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] By moving forward, the batter is also able to intercept the ball immediately after it has pitched, thus nullifying any potentially dangerous lateral movement.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A back foot shot is typically used to address a ball arriving at between thigh and head height.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The batter will step back and, if necessary, stand on their tiptoes to raise the bat to the height of the ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] By stepping back towards the wicket, the batter also receives the advantage of having an extra small amount of time to react to any unexpected lateral movement or variation in bounce.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Vertical-bat or straight-bat shots can be played off either the front foot or the back foot depending upon the anticipated height of the ball at the moment it reaches the batter.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The characteristic position of the bat is a vertical alignment at the point of contact.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Vertical-bat shots are typically played with the batter's head directly above the point of contact so they are able to accurately judge the line of the ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] At this point, the bat can either be stationary and facing straight back down the wicket – known as a block or defensive shot; angled to one side – known as a glance or deflection; or travelling forwards towards the bowler – known as a drive.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A *block* stroke is usually a purely defensive stroke designed to stop the ball from hitting the wicket or the batter's body.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] This shot has no strength behind it and is usually played with a light or "soft" grip (commentators often refer to "soft hands") and merely stops the ball moving towards the wicket.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A block played on the front foot is known as a *forward defensive*, while that played on the back foot is known as a *backward defensive*.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] These strokes may be used to score runs, by manipulating the block to move the ball into vacant portions of the infield, in which case a block becomes a "push".
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Pushing the ball is one of the more common ways batters manipulate the strike.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Leaving and blocking are employed much more often in first-class cricket (including Test matches), as there is no requirement to score runs as quickly as possible, thus allowing the batter to choose which deliveries to play.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A *leg glance* is a delicate straight-batted shot played at a ball aimed slightly on the leg side, using the bat to flick the ball as it passes the batter, and requiring some wrist work as well, deflecting towards the square leg or fine leg area.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The stroke involves deflecting the bat-face towards the leg side at the last moment, head and body moving inside the line of the ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] This shot is played "off the toes, shins or hip".
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It is played off the front foot if the ball is pitched up at the toes or shin of the batter, or off the back foot if the ball bounces at waist/hip height to the batter.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Although the opposite term *off glance* is not employed within cricket, the concept of angling the bat face towards the offside to deflect the ball away from the wicket for the purpose of scoring runs through the off side is a commonly used technique.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] This would commonly be described instead as "running (or steering) the ball down to the third man".
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The *leave* is sometimes considered a cricket shot, even though the batter physically does not even touch the ball as it passes them.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The leave is often used by a batter during the first few balls they receive, to give them time to judge the conditions of the pitch and the bowling before attempting to play a shot.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Leaving a delivery is a matter of judgement and technique.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The batter still has to watch the ball closely to ensure that it will not hit them or the wicket; they also have to ensure that their bat and hands are kept out of the path of the ball so that it cannot make accidental contact and possibly lead to them being out caught.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Batters only leave the ball when they are certain that it will not hit the stumps.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A *drive* is a straight-batted shot, played by swinging the bat in a vertical arc through the line of the ball, hitting the ball in front of the batter along the ground.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It is one of the most common shots in a batter's armory and often the first shot taught to junior cricketers.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Depending on the direction the ball travels, a drive can be a *cover drive* (struck towards the cover fielding position), an *off drive* (towards mid-off), *straight drive* (straight past the bowler), *on drive* (between stumps and mid-on) or *square drive* (towards point).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A drive can also be played towards midwicket, although the phrase "midwicket drive" is not in common usage.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Drives can be played both off the front and the back foot, but back-foot drives are harder to force through the line of the ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Although most drives are deliberately struck along the ground to reduce the risk of being dismissed caught, a batter may decide to play a *lofted drive* to hit the ball over the infielders and potentially even over the boundary for six.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A *flick* shot is a shot played on the leg side by flicking a full-length delivery using the wrists.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The shot is played with the bat coming through straight as for the on drive, but the bat face is angled towards the leg side.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It can be played both off the front foot or the back foot, either off the toes or from the hips.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The shot is played between the mid-on and square leg region.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Typically played along the ground, the flick can also be played by lofting the ball over the infield.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The second class of cricket stroke comprises the horizontal-bat shots, also known as cross-bat shots: the cut, the square drive, the pull, the hook, and the sweep.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Typically, horizontal bat shots have a greater probability of failing to make contact with the ball than vertical bat shots and therefore are restricted to deliveries that are not threatening to hit the stumps, either by dint of being too wide or too short.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The bat is swung in a horizontal arc, with the batter's head typically not being perfectly in line with the ball at the point of contact.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A *cut* is a cross-batted shot played at a short-pitched ball, placing it wide on the off side.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The batter makes contact with the ball as it draws alongside or passes them and therefore requires virtually no effort on their part as they use the bowler's pace to divert the ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A *square cut* is a shot hit into the off side at near to 90 degrees from the wicket (towards point).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A *late cut* is played as or after the ball passes the batter's body and is hit towards the third man position.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The cut shot is typically played off the back foot but is also sometimes played off the front foot against slower bowling.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The cut should be played with the face of the bat rolling over the ball to face the ground thus pushing the ball downwards.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A mistimed cut with an open-faced bat (with the face of the bat facing the bowler) will generally lead to the ball rising in the air, giving a chance for the batter to be caught.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Although confusingly named a drive, the square drive is actually a horizontal bat shot, with identical arm mechanics to that of the square cut.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A *pull* is a cross-batted shot played to a ball bouncing around waist height by swinging the bat in a horizontal arc in front of the body, *pulling* it around to the leg side towards mid-wicket or square leg.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The term *hook* shot is used when the shot is played against a ball bouncing at or above chest high to the batter, the batter thus "hooking" the ball around behind square leg, either along the ground or in the air.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Pull and hook shots can be played off the front or back foot, with the back foot being more typical.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A *paddle sweep* shot is a sweep shot in which the ball is deflected towards fine leg with a stationary or near-stationary bat extended horizontally towards the bowler, whereas the hard sweep shot is played towards square leg with the bat swung firmly in a horizontal arc.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Typically the sweep shot will be played to a legside delivery, but it is also possible for a batter to sweep the ball to the leg side from outside off stump.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Attempting to sweep a full straight delivery on the stumps is generally not recommended because of the risk of lbw.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Since a batter is free to play any shot to any type of delivery as they wish, the above list is by no means a complete list of the strokes that batters choose to play.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Many unorthodox, typically high-risk, shots have been used throughout the history of the game.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The advent of limited overs cricket has seen the increased use of unorthodox shots to hit the ball into gaps where there are no fielders placed.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Unorthodox shots are rarely used in first-class cricket as the pace of the game is slower and it is relatively more important to keep one's wicket than to try to score runs off every ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A few unorthodox shots have gained enough popularity or notoriety to have been given their own names and entered common usage.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A reverse sweep is a cross-batted sweep shot played in the opposite direction to the standard sweep, thus instead of sweeping the ball to the leg side, it is swept to the off side, towards a *backward point* or *third man*.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The batter may also swap their hands on the bat handle to make the stroke easier to execute.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The batter may also bring their back foot to the front, therefore, turning the shot into a switch-hit and making it more like a traditional sweep.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The advantage of a reverse sweep is that it effectively reverses the fielding positions and thus is very difficult to set a field to.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It is also a risky shot for the batter as it increases the chance of lbw and also is quite easy to *top edge* to a fielder.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It was first regularly played in the 1970s by the Pakistani batter Mushtaq Mohammad, though Mushtaq's brother Hanif Mohammad is sometimes credited as the inventor.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Cricket coach Bob Woolmer has been credited with popularising the stroke.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The most famous example of a reverse sweep backfiring was in the case of Mike Gatting of England against Allan Border of Australia in the 1987 Cricket World Cup Final.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] With England on course for victory, Gatting attempted a reverse sweep off the first delivery bowled by Border, top-edged the ball and was caught by wicketkeeper Greg Dyer.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] England subsequently lost momentum and eventually lost the match.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Because of the unorthodox nature of hand and body position, it is often difficult to get a lot of power behind a reverse sweep; in many situations, the intention is to glance or cut the ball to the back leg area.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] However, on rare occasions, players have been able to execute reverse sweeps for a six.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Kevin Pietersen, who pioneered switch-hitting, is adept at this, but one could argue that the resulting shot is basically a sweep rather than a reverse sweep.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A more classic example of such a shot would be Yusuf Pathan's six off Robin Peterson.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] South Africa's AB de Villiers is well known for his ability to hit sixes with the reverse sweep at ease and Glenn Maxwell also often plays the reverse sweep.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A *slog* is a powerful pull shot played over mid-wicket, usually, hit in the air in an attempt to score a six.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A shot would be referred to as a slog when it is typically played at a delivery that would not ordinarily be pulled.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A slog can also be described as hitting the ball to "cow corner".
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] This phrase is designed to imply that the batter is unsophisticated in their stroke play and technique by suggesting they would be more at home playing on more rudimentary cricket fields in which there may be cows grazing along the boundary edge.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The slog can be an effective shot because all the batter's power and body weight can be put into swinging the bat at the ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A *slog sweep* is a slog played from the kneeling position used to sweep.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Slog sweeps are usually directed over square-leg rather than to mid-wicket.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It is almost exclusively used against reasonably full-pitched balls from slow bowlers, as only then does the batter have time to sight the length and adopt the kneeling position required for the slog sweep.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The front leg of the shot is usually placed wider outside leg stump to allow for a full swing of the bat.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] An *upper cut* is a shot played towards *third man*, usually hit when the ball is pitched outside the *off stump* with extra bounce.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It is a dangerous shot which can *edge* the ball to keeper or slips if not executed correctly.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The shot is widely used in modern cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The shot is advantageous on fast bouncy tracks and is seen commonly in Twenty20 cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Notable players who used the upper cut include Sachin Tendulkar, Virender Sehwag and Brendan Taylor.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A *switch hit* is a shot where a batter changes their handedness and posture to adopt a stance the mirror image of their traditional handedness while the bowler is running in to bowl.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] As a fielding team cannot manoeuvre fielders while the bowler is in their run-up, the fielding side is effectively wrong-footed with the fielders out of position.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The shot was pioneered by Kevin Pietersen, first performed off the bowling of Muttiah Muralitharan in England's 2006 home series against Sri Lanka.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It was subsequently used in the New Zealand series in England in 2008 when Pietersen performed the shot twice in the same over against Scott Styris on his way to making an unbeaten century.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] David Warner, the Australian opener, is also a frequent user of the switch hit and used it to great effect against the Indian off-spinner Ravichandran Ashwin in the first Twenty20 of the Indian cricket team's tour to Australia 2012.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Glenn Maxwell and Ben Stokes also play the switch hit.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The legality of the switch hit was questioned when first introduced but cleared by the International Cricket Council as legal.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The shot is risky because a batter is less proficient in the other handedness and is more likely to make a mistake in the execution of the shot.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A *scoop* shot has been used by a number of first-class players.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It is played to short-pitched straight balls that would traditionally be defended or, more aggressively, pulled to the leg side.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] To play a scoop shot, the batter is on the front foot and aims to get beneath the bounce of the ball and hit it directly behind the stumps, up and over the wicket-keeper.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] This shot, though risky in the execution, has the advantage of being aimed at a section of the field where a fielder is rarely placed – particularly in Twenty20 and One Day International cricket where the number of outfielders is limited.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] However, the Marillier shot is played over the batter's shoulder to fine leg, but the basis of the scoop stroke is for the batter to go down on one knee to a good length or slightly short-of-length delivery off a fast or medium paced bowler and scoop the ball over the head of the wicket-keeper.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The scoop shot is a risky shot to play as the improper execution of this shot may lead to a catch being offered.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A version of the scoop stroke called the *Dilscoop* was developed by Sri Lankan right-handed batter Tillakaratne Dilshan during the 2009 ICC World Twenty20.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The *helicopter shot* is the act of hitting the ball by means of a wristy flick, using the bottom-hand as the dominant force.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The shot gets its name from the flourish completing the stroke, with the bat being circled overhead.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The shot got its fame through MS Dhoni, who played it on a regular basis as a way to score boundaries against full and yorker length deliveries.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The *French cut* is a stroke where the ball is hit with the inside edge of the bat, meaning it is directed between the batter and the stumps, and moves away in the direction of the fine leg fielding position.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The stroke is very difficult to play intentionally, and is more often a mistake by the batter.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It is a risky stroke, and can easily result in the batter playing on to their stumps, resulting in the batter being dismissed as bowled.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The fundamental aim of each batter is to find a means of safely scoring runs against each bowler they face.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] To do this, the batter must take into consideration the bowler's strategy, the position of the fielders, the pitch conditions, and their own strengths and weaknesses.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The strategy they will decide on will incorporate a number of preconceived attacking responses to the various deliveries they may anticipate receiving, designed specifically to score runs with minimal risk of being dismissed.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The success of this strategy will be dependent upon both the accuracy of its conception and the technical ability with which it is carried out.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A key aspect of the strategy of batting is the trade-off between the level of aggression (trying to score) and the risk involved of being dismissed.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] An optimal batting strategy balances several considerations: the number of wickets left, the target that has been set (if batting last) and how the risk of losing a wicket increase when increasing the strike rate.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] These strategies depend on the match situation and on the match format.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Strategies therefore vary greatly between the three forms of international cricket: Test, One Day International and T20 cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] In Test cricket, the usual aim is to score as high a total as possible.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] As the overs are unlimited, a batter can take their time to score runs.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] In general, 90 overs have to be bowled per day in Test match cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The first-drop batter is usually also chosen for their sound technique, so as to stabilise their end in case an opener gets out.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The middle order of a batting team in Test matches usually includes its most skilled batters in terms of shot-playing ability, because during the middle overs of a day batting is relatively easier than in the initial stages of the innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] If the batting innings of a team begins after the last half-hour of the day, the team might employ a nightwatchman to bat after a dismissal.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The *nightwatchman* is usually a lower-order player, able to protect their wicket primarily by defending dangerous balls and leaving non-dangerous ones rather than looking to produce a large number of runs for their team, but not a complete rabbit, liable to expose other players late in a day.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] In the third innings, the batting team may score quickly to set a large target to the opposition.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] This scenario usually occurs on the fourth day's play.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The batting captain decides how many overs they are prepared to allow the opposition to chase the batting team's total in their fourth innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The captain usually declares their team's innings at a predetermined time on the fourth day so they can bowl at least 20 overs on that day and 90 overs on the last day.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A good number of overs to bowl at the opposition team in the fourth innings is essential because usually on the fourth and fifth days of a Test match conditions are good for bowling (especially slow bowling), with the pitch having experienced a fair degree of wear and tear.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Thus, to make the target as difficult as possible, the batting side speeds up the run rate (runs per over) until the captain declares.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] If, however, a batting team is significantly behind the opposition in terms of runs going into the fourth day of a Test match, a typical strategy by the batting team involves playing defensively to avoid losing their wickets.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] This ensures that they occupy the most time until the match draws to a close on the fifth day, because if a team's innings does not end on the fifth day then the match is *drawn*, or a stalemate is reached.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] As One Day International matches have a limited set of overs, batters try to score quickly.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Doing so, batters should aim for a higher run rate than the one which would maximise their expected personal score.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It is optimal for batters to take the risk of being dismissed and being replaced by another teammate.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] This higher risk strategy makes the best of the limited number of overs.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Scoring quickly typically means trying to score at least one run per ball bowled.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Most batter manage to score at an average of four runs an over (i.e. four runs in the six ball over).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The optimal level of risk should vary depending on different factors.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It should be higher when the team has more wickets left as they provide of a cushion of security (against the risk of ending all out).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It should be higher when the pitch provides good conditions for batting, making it easier to score without great risk of being dismissed.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] It should increase towards the end of the innings when the number of overs left is small (there is not much to lose in taking the risk of ending all out).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Research has shown that teams broadly follow these principles.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] A noticeable exception is when batters face the possibility of scoring a personal milestone (e.g. century), in that case, they tend to decrease their risk-taking below what is optimal for the team in order to increase their chance of reaching the milestone.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] When a team goes out to bat, the best players bat first.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The first three batters (number 1, 2, 3) are known as the *top order*; the next four (numbers 4, 5, 6 and possibly 7) form the *middle order*, and the last four (numbers 8, 9, 10 and 11) are the *lower order* or *tail*.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The specialist batters of a team usually bat near the top of the order, so as to score more runs.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The *openers* or opening batter are the first two players to take the crease.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] They are not necessarily the best batters, but are expected to negotiate the new ball and not lose wickets until the shine on the ball is considerably diminished (a hard and shiny ball bounces and swings more and is more difficult for the batter to face).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] In addition, they are supposed to play quick innings (more runs in fewer balls), reflecting the fact that the fielding side is subject to restrictions on the placement of fielders in the first 15 overs which makes it easier to score runs.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] In a recent amendment to the rules of ODI cricket, fielding captains are given mandatory fielding restrictions for the first 10 overs and then two chunks of 5 overs each, also known as *power-play* overs, which they may impose at any stage of their choice within the stipulated 50 overs.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Their job is to take over from the openers and typically play a careful and prolonged innings, effectively tying up one end of the batting.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] This brings in some stability in the batting, as new batters find it difficult to settle down and it helps to have a settled player at the other end.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The best batter of the team is usually put at number 3 or 4, to protect them from the difficulties of batting against the best bowlers on a fresh pitch and to allow them to play long innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The middle order is often considered the most valuable asset of a batting line-up in One-Day Internationals because its members are responsible for consolidating the batting team's position through the middle part of the 50 overs.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Characteristic of middle-order batting is the practice of taking many *singles* (or *ones*) and 'twos', with only the occasional *boundary* (a four or a six), as opposed to the more flamboyant openers who score primarily in boundaries.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] This is because the fielding restrictions on the opposition are lifted in the middle overs so that the percentage of boundaries scored decreases.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Middle-order players are often chosen for the ability to run hard and fast between the wickets (to maximise the number of runs not scored from boundaries) and for their endurance and patience.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The middle order typically sets the stage for an aggressive assault on the bowling in the final 10 overs of the match.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] To achieve this assault, two things are necessary – a number of hard-hitting players yet to bat or not out and a number of wickets in hand (since aggression means a greater likelihood of losing wickets).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] The last 10 overs of a one-day cricket match innings is often the most exciting part of the innings, because of a large number of boundaries scored and wickets taken.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] During the last ten overs of an ODI, batters often use shots that are riskier than shots played at the beginning of the innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Examples of risky shots include the reverse sweep and the paddle-scoop.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] These shots are used to achieve a boundary which would not be possible when playing a safer, more orthodox shot.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Finally, the lower order consists of the bowlers of the team, who are not known for their batting prowess and so bat as low down the order as possible.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] However, there are no real restrictions to the batting positions.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Captains have been known to experiment with the batting line-up to gain specific advantages.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] When batting, a batter has to balance opportunities to score runs by running between the popping creases with the risk of being run out (or even stumped, if batting outside their crease).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Batting partners must agree on each run they take, or else one of them is likely to be out of their ground and thus run out.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Sometimes batters take risks by running even when the fielder has the ball in hand, and is in a position to throw the ball at the wicket; this is known as "taking on the arm of the fielder".
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] This can occasionally lead to overthrows.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Batters often slide headfirst with their bat outstretched to make their ground.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-cricket] Being able to run faster to score more runs, as well as improve endurance so as to not be fatigued by running a lot throughout a long innings (which could disrupt the concentration or strength needed for batting), is part of the athletic training for batters.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] In cricket, the **batting order** is the sequence in which batters play through their team's innings, there always being two batters taking part at any one time.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] All eleven players in a team are required to bat if the innings is completed (i.e., if the innings does not close early due to a declaration or other factor).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The order in which the eleven players will bat is usually established before the start of a cricket match, but may be altered during play.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Also, a middle-order batter in Tests may open for ODIs and Twenty20 due to their aggressive approach to the game.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The captain of the team can change the batting order during the game at their discretion.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] They can even change the batting line-up from one game to another in a tournament or series.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] There are no rules about the nature or number of changes made and, if more than one innings is played, the order used in each need not be the same.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] It has even been known for a captain to completely reverse his batting order for the second innings after following on.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] This has made it possible for a bowler to take a hat-trick across three consecutive overs of a match, including the same batter twice.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] There are various reasons why the captain might make a change from the established order.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Usually, however, captains and coaches prefer not to adjust the batting order unless necessary, as for example when South Africa moved Imran Tahir up the order against India because the South African top seven batters were poor against spin bowlers.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] In 2017, Faf du Plessis, who returned to the side as Test Captain after paternity leave, decided to make many changes to the batting lineup before the second test against England after being handed a heavy defeat.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] 5, and moved Quinton de Kock from 5 to 4 (de Kock already moved from no.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] 7 to 5 between the 1st and 2nd innings of the first Test), and due to the suspension of Kagiso Rabada due to demerit points, so Duanne Olivier replaced him, Philander moved up a spot to no.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] 7, while Theunis de Bruyn was replaced by Chris Morris at no.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The Indian cricket team also shuffled their batting order in the first ODI of the India tour of West Indies and United States, 2023.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] In the days before covered pitches, a particularly bad sticky wicket might see each team reverse the batting order to trade the wickets of their inferior batters for the time it could take for the unpredictability of the pitch to die down.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Don Bradman has the highest test score as a #7 batsman after such a reversal of the order.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] If the state of the game requires runs to be scored quickly, a captain will often promote a batter who is known to score quickly up the order.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] This is usually a lower-order batter, as their wicket is not regarded as being so valuable.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] A batter who is promoted up the order with the intention of scoring quick runs is called a pinch hitter or slogger.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Some examples of pinch hitters include David Miller, Mitchell Starc, Shahid Afridi and Thisara Perera.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] In the West Indies' 2020 tour of England, during the second Test, England captain Joe Root sent Jos Buttler and Ben Stokes, two middle order batters known for quick scoring, up to open; the reason being England needed to score quickly in order to force a result despite rain.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Stokes finished on 78* as England declared, while Buttler fell in the first over, having failed to score.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] When a wicket falls near the end of the day, a lower order (less capable) batter might be sent in to bat with the intention that the more capable players will be held in reserve until the next morning.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The more capable players are then not exposed to the risk of dismissal while tired or in low-light conditions.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The batter who is sent in is known as the nightwatchman.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] This tactic is also used because players are typically nervous and unsettled at the start of the innings before settling into their rhythm and becoming "set".
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Sending a specialist batter in late in the day means that the batter will have to survive one such period in the afternoon, before doing the same again after the resumption of play the next day, increasing the chance of a dismissal, so a less valuable batter is sent in instead.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] However, some nightwatchmen do go on to make big scores, most notably Jason Gillespie's 201* at number three (he usually batted at nine or ten) against Bangladesh in 2006.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The **opening batters** or **openers** are the batters who bat first in the innings (no.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] This position is very important as the openers need to get the innings off to a good start.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The early fall of wickets can have a serious psychological impact on the rest of the team, affecting their performance with the bat.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The opening batters also get the first experience of the pitch and conditions and must be able to adjust to them quickly.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Due to this, they are able to inform other batters of the state of the pitch as well.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Most importantly, the opening batters must face a new ball, which is hard and has a pronounced seam.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] This makes it more liable to travel fast, bounce high, seam around (i.e., bounce unpredictably off the seam) and swing (i.e., deviate sideways when travelling through the air).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] These early conditions favour the bowling team, so the opening batters must have considerable patience, a sound technique and be good defensively.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] As the ball gets older, its condition starts to favour the batting team.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Therefore, the openers will ideally stay at the crease long enough to protect the batters further down the order.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] In first-class cricket, the rate at which the openers score runs is not as important as "taking the shine off" the new ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] This is the process of softening and roughening the cricket ball, whose condition tends to degrade the longer it is in play.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] By occupying the crease for a long time and taking the shine off the ball, the openers themselves are able to score more freely later on.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] This also makes batting easier for the rest of the order.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Because of the defensive technique required early on, openers are sometimes less fluent stroke-players than the specialist batters who follow.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] In limited overs cricket, the role of opening batter is slightly different.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] In this type of cricket a high run rate is a necessity.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Also, in the early 1990s, fielding restrictions were introduced in the early overs of the game, limiting the fielding side to only two players on the boundary.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] To start the innings effectively and take advantage of the fielding restrictions, it became beneficial to have an aggressive batter opening the innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Due to these differences, there are examples of batsmen who would ordinarily play down in the lower order, such as a wicket-keeper batsman in First Class and Test Match cricket or heavy hitting all-rounders, being elevated to open in limited overs cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Adam Gilchrist batted in a 6, 7 or 8 position batter for all but a handful of his Test innings but in One Day Internationals he opened over 260 times.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] If an opening batter remains not out at the end of the team's innings, after all 10 other batters have been dismissed, he or she is said to have carried the bat.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The **top order** is defined as the batters batting at positions 1, 2 and 3.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The batters who bat at positions 1, 2 and 3 in the order are sometimes the most technically proficient batters with the best stroke play.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] They generally face new ball, and are expected to give a good start of the innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Top and middle order batters must also be adaptable as they may be required to attack, consolidate or defend according to the needs of the team as the match situation develops.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The **middle order** is typically defined as the batters batting at positions 4, 5, 6, 7, and sometimes 8.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] It usually consists of versatile batters who must continue to build an innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The middle order batter is likely to be facing a much older ball bowled by a spin bowler and defensive technique is necessary to overcome this type of attack, but they are often also fleet-footed players who attack slow bowling by charging down the pitch.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The middle order players must also be adept at making runs when playing with the poor quality batters in the lower order.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] This requires the ability to manipulate the strike so that the tail-enders are shielded from the more potent bowlers.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Players who are designated as an all-rounder often bat in the middle order (e.g.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Garfield Sobers usually batted at number 6; by contrast, W.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Grace always opened the innings). wicket-keepers generally bat in the middle order as well, often at number 6 or 7 (e.g.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Adam Gilchrist throughout his Test career usually batted at number 7; however he predominantly opened the batting in limited-overs cricket).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] One reason for placing all-rounders and wicket-keepers in the middle-order even though they may be more skilled than those who batted above them was because such players would be tired after bowling or keeping wicket during the preceding innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] It is also plausible to see substitute wicket-keepers batting at number 5 or 6.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] In One Day International cricket, middle order batters are generally able to change their game depending on the conditions.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] If their team loses wickets early, they must be able to play a long careful innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Conversely, if they are not required to bat until later in the game, they must be able to attempt to score quickly, often attempting to hit many fours or sixes, and if they only have a short period to bat, they are expected to be innovative and able to settle after a short period.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] In run-chases they are required to be good at calculating and minimising the risks needed to reach the target, by scoring at close to the rate required.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] If they score more quickly than is required, they run the risk of getting out and exposing the weaker, lower-order batters to the pressure situation, but if they score too slowly, then they fall behind schedule and the pressure again increases.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Australian player Michael Bevan was known during his player career by the nickname of "The Finisher", leading the ICC batting rankings multiple times, and helping Australia to numerous wins from his bat.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Examples of this finishing style include the 1996 World Cup Semi-Final against the West Indies where Bevan and Stuart Law were at the crease with Australia having lost 4 wickets for just 15 runs in the 9th over.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Law stayed in until the 41st over scoring 72 and Bevan the 44th over with 69 as Australia eventually scored 207 and the West Indies collapsed late in the match to fall 5 runs short.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The **lower order** is defined as the batters batting at positions 8 (sometimes), 9, 10 and 11.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] It is usually made up of players who have poorer batting skills compared to others in the team or new team members who are often placed there before they prove themselves a worthy batter; they are commonly known as **tailenders** (**tail ender** or **tail-ender**).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] These players are the team's specialist bowlers and sometimes the wicketkeeper, or even players on debut if their batting abilities are unproven.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Bowlers with better batting abilities, aspiring all-rounders, or wicketkeepers do have a chance to move up the order over the course of their careers (notably Steve Smith moved from 7 to 3 or 4, and Ashton Agar moved from 11 to 7 in first-class cricket).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] However, some bowlers establish themselves as competent lower order batters, especially at no.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] 8 where many bowlers become bowling all-rounders, as in the case of fast bowlers Wasim Akram and Jason Holder, both of whom have a Test double century each to their names.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] By the same token, opening batters could move down the order due to poor form, having a top-heavy line-up or being better suited to play against spin bowling (notably Moeen Ali moving down from an opener to no.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] 7, or even 8, since the 2015 Ashes series, but has since also played at 3 in 2018).
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Therefore, the start of the lower order may vary in position depending on the balance of the side in terms of overall batting capability.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Also, given that batters in ODIs and Twenty20 need to score quickly and aggressively, an opener in limited-overs forms of the game may bat down the order in Tests.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] A batting lineup containing more bowlers than usual may be described as having a "long tail".
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] It is likely that these batters will be dismissed for low scores.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] However, as expectations of these players are low when they are batting, they often play aggressive, carefree shots in the hope of scoring as many runs as possible.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] On occasion, the scores posted by the lower order have made a difference to the outcome of a match.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] If a significant contribution has come from the tail-enders, it is often said that "the tail wagged".
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] On occasions in which the batting team is a long way behind its opponents, the lower-order batters may attempt to salvage a draw by playing defensively until the end of the match.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] An example of this would be the first test in the 2009 Ashes series, in which England bowlers James Anderson and Monty Panesar were able to remain at the crease for 11.3 overs, denying Australia the chance to win the match.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] The last batter in the order (at position 11) is sometimes referred to as *Last Man Jack*, a term that has passed into everyday parlance.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] This is because if the batting order were arranged as a pack of cards numbers 9 and 10 would be followed by Jack.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Those batters who bat at positions 8 and 9 are also known as middle–lower order batters.
[src:fielding-cricket/batting-order-cricket] Source: Nitschke's score of 81 and Smith's 42 in the 2005 Women's Ashes in a partnership of 139 is the highest last wicket partnership in women's test cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] At the time, no helmets or other upper-body protective gear was worn, and critics of the tactic considered it intimidating, and physically threatening in a game traditionally supposed to uphold conventions of sportsmanship.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The England team's use of the tactic was perceived by some, both in Australia and England, as overly aggressive or even unfair.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] It caused a controversy that rose to such a level that it threatened diplomatic relations between the two countries before the situation was calmed.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Although no serious injuries arose from any short-pitched deliveries while a leg theory field was set, the tactic led to considerable ill feeling between the two teams, particularly when Australian batsmen were struck, inflaming spectators.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] After the introduction of helmets, short-pitched fast bowling, sometimes exceeding 90 miles per hour (140 km/h), continues to be permitted in cricket, even when aimed at the batsman, and is considered to be a legitimate bowling tactic when used sparingly.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Over time, several Laws of Cricket were changed to render the bodyline tactic less effective—and increase player safety—such as a legside field restriction, concussion breaks and inspections.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Bodyline is a tactic devised for and primarily used in the Ashes series between England and Australia in 1932–33.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The tactic involved bowling at the leg stump or just outside it, but pitching the ball short so that, on bouncing, it reared up threateningly at the body of a batsman standing in an orthodox batting position.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] A ring of fielders ranged on the leg side would catch any defensive deflection from the bat.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The batsman's options were to evade the ball through ducking or moving aside, allow the ball to strike his body, or attempt to play the ball with his bat.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The last course carried additional risks, as defensive shots brought few runs and could carry far enough to be caught by fielders on the leg side, and pull and hook shots could be caught near the boundary of the field where two men were usually placed for such a shot.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Bodyline bowling is intended to be intimidatory, and it was primarily designed as an attempt to curb the unusually prolific scoring of Don Bradman, although other Australian batsmen such as Bill Woodfull, Bill Ponsford, and Alan Kippax were also targeted.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Several terms were used to describe this style of bowling before the name 'bodyline' was used.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Among the first to use it was the writer and former Australian Test cricketer Jack Worrall in the match between the English team and an Australian XI.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] When 'bodyline' was first used in full, he referred to "half-pitched slingers on the body line" and first used it in print after the first Test.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Other writers used a similar phrase around this time, but the first use of 'bodyline' in print seems to have been by the journalist Hugh Buggy in the Melbourne *Herald*, in his report on the first day's play of the first Test.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] In the 19th century, most cricketers considered it unsportsmanlike to bowl the ball at the leg stump or for batsmen to hit on the leg side.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] But by the early years of the 20th century, some bowlers, usually slow or medium-paced, used leg theory as a tactic; the ball was aimed outside the line of leg stump and the fielders placed on that side of the field, the object being to test the batsman's patience and force a rash stroke.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Two English left-arm bowlers, George Hirst in 1903–04 and Frank Foster in 1911–12, bowled leg theory to packed leg side fields in Test matches in Australia; Warwick Armstrong also used it regularly for Australia.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] In the years immediately before the First World War, several bowlers used leg theory in English county cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Amongst these was the South African Basil Melle, who utilised leg theory bowling playing for Oxford University during the 1913 season, in which he took 55 wickets and in The University Match dominated the Cambridge University batsmen.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] When cricket resumed after the war, few bowlers maintained the tactic, which was unpopular with spectators owing to its negativity.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Fred Root, the Worcestershire bowler, used it regularly and with considerable success in county cricket.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Root later defended the use of leg theory—and bodyline—observing that when bowlers bowled outside off stump, the batsmen always had the option to let the ball pass them without playing a shot, so they could scarcely complain.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Some fast bowlers experimented with leg theory prior to 1932, sometimes accompanying the tactic with short-pitched bowling.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] In 1925, Australian Jack Scott first bowled a form of what would later have been called bodyline in a state match for New South Wales; his captain Herbie Collins disliked it and would not let him use it again.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Other Australian captains were less particular, including Vic Richardson, who asked the South Australian bowler Lance Gun to use it in 1925, and later let Scott use it when he moved to South Australia.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Scott repeated the tactics against the MCC in 1928–29.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] In 1927, in a Test trial match, "Nobby" Clark bowled short to a leg-trap (a cluster of fielders placed close on the leg side).
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] He was representing England in a side captained by Douglas Jardine.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] In 1928–29, Harry Alexander bowled fast leg theory at an England team, and Harold Larwood briefly used a similar tactic on that same tour in two Test matches.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Freddie Calthorpe, the England captain, criticised Learie Constantine's use of short-pitched bowling to a leg side field in a Test match in 1930; one such ball struck Andy Sandham, but Constantine only reverted to more conventional tactics after a complaint from the England team.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The Australian cricket team toured England in 1930.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Australia won the five-Test series 2–1, and Bradman scored 974 runs at a batting average of 139.14, an aggregate record that still stands to this day.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] By the time of the next Ashes series of 1932–33, Bradman's average hovered around 100, approximately twice that of all other world-class batsmen.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Gradually, the idea developed that Bradman was possibly vulnerable to pace bowling.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] In the final Test of the 1930 Ashes series, while he was batting, the pitch became briefly difficult following rain.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Bradman was observed to be uncomfortable facing deliveries which bounced higher than usual at a faster pace, being seen to consistently step back out of the line of the ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Former England player and Surrey captain Percy Fender was one who noticed this, and the incident was much discussed by cricketers.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Given that Bradman scored 232, it was not initially thought that a way to curb his prodigious scoring had been found.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] When Douglas Jardine later saw film footage of the Oval incident and noticed Bradman's discomfort, according to his daughter he shouted, "I've got it!
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] He's yellow!" The theory of Bradman's vulnerability developed further when Fender received correspondence from Australia in 1932, describing how Australian batsmen were increasingly moving across the stumps towards the off side to play the ball on the on side.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Fender showed these letters to his Surrey team-mate Jardine when it became clear that Jardine was to captain the English team in Australia during the 1932–33 tour, and he also discussed Bradman's discomfort at the Oval.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] It was also known in England that Bradman was dismissed for a four-ball duck by fast bowler Eddie Gilbert, and had looked very uncomfortable.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Fender felt Bradman might be vulnerable to fast, short-pitched deliveries on the line of leg stump.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Jardine felt that Bradman was nervous about standing his ground against intimidatory bowling, citing instances in 1930 when he shuffled about, contrary to orthodox batting technique.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Jardine's first experience against Australia came when he scored an unbeaten 96 to secure a draw against the 1921 Australian touring side for Oxford University.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The tourists were criticised in the press for not allowing Jardine to reach his hundred, but had tried to help him with some easy bowling.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] There has been speculation that this incident helped develop Jardine's antipathy towards Australians, although Jardine's biographer Christopher Douglas denies this.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Jardine's attitude towards Australia hardened after he toured the country in 1928–29.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Although Jardine may simply have worn the cap out of superstition, it conveyed a negative impression to the spectators; his general demeanour drew one comment of "Where's the butler to carry the bat for you?" By this stage Jardine had developed an intense dislike for Australian crowds.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] During his third century at the start of the tour, during a period of abuse from the spectators, he observed to Hunter Hendry that "All Australians are uneducated, and an unruly mob".
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] After the innings, when teammate Patsy Hendren remarked that the Australian crowds did not like Jardine, he replied "It's fucking mutual".
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] During the tour, Jardine fielded next to the crowd on the boundary.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] There, he was roundly abused and mocked for his awkward fielding, particularly when chasing the ball.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] On one occasion, he spat towards the crowd while fielding on the boundary as he changed position for the final time.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Jardine was appointed captain of England for the 1931 season, replacing Percy Chapman who had led the team in 1930.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] He defeated New Zealand in his first series, but opinion was divided as to how effective he had been.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The following season, he led England again and was appointed to lead the team to tour Australia for the 1932–33 Ashes series.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] A meeting was arranged between Jardine, Nottinghamshire captain Arthur Carr and his two fast bowlers Harold Larwood and Bill Voce at London's Piccadilly Hotel to discuss a plan to combat Bradman.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Jardine asked Larwood and Voce if they could bowl on leg stump and make the ball rise into the body of the batsman.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The bowlers agreed they could, and that it might prove effective.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Jardine also visited Frank Foster to discuss his field-placing in Australia in 1911–12.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Larwood and Voce practised the plan over the remainder of the 1932 season with varying but increasing success and several injuries to batsmen.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Ken Farnes experimented with short-pitched, leg-theory bowling but was not selected for the tour.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Bill Bowes also used short-pitched bowling, notably against Jack Hobbs.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The England team which toured Australia in 1932–33 contained four fast bowlers and a few medium pacers; such a heavy concentration on pace was unusual at the time, and drew comment from the Australian press and players, including Bradman.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] On the journey, Jardine instructed his team on how to approach the tour and discussed tactics with several players, including Larwood; at this stage, he seems to have settled on leg theory, if not full bodyline, as his main tactic.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Some players later reported that he told them to hate the Australians in order to defeat them, while instructing them to refer to Bradman as "the little bastard." Upon arrival, Jardine quickly alienated the press and crowds through his manner and approach.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] In the early matches, although there were instances of the English bowlers pitching the ball short and causing problems with their pace, full bodyline tactics were not used.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] There had been little unusual about the English bowling except the number of fast bowlers.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Larwood and Voce were given a light workload in the early matches by Jardine.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The English tactics changed in a game against an Australian XI team at Melbourne in mid-November, when full bodyline tactics were deployed for the first time.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Jardine had left himself out of the English side, which was led instead by Bob Wyatt who later wrote that the team experimented with a diluted form of bodyline bowling.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] He reported to Jardine that Bradman, who was playing for the opposition, seemed uncomfortable against the bowling tactics of Larwood, Voce and Bowes.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The crowd, press and Australian players were shocked by what they experienced and believed that the bowlers were targeting the batsmen's heads.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Bradman adopted unorthodox tactics—ducking, weaving and moving around the crease—which did not meet with universal approval from Australians and he scored just 36 and 13 in the match.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The tactic continued to be used in the next game by Voce (Larwood and Bowes did not play in this game), against New South Wales, for whom Jack Fingleton made a century and received several blows in the process.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Bradman again failed twice, and had scored just 103 runs in six innings against the touring team; many Australian fans were now worried by Bradman's form.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The Australian press were shocked and criticised the hostility of Larwood in particular.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Some former Australian players joined the criticism, saying the tactics were ethically wrong.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] But at this stage, not everyone was opposed, and the Australian Board of Control believed the English team had bowled fairly.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] On the other hand, Jardine increasingly came into disagreement with tour manager Warner over bodyline as the tour progressed.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Warner hated bodyline but would not speak out against it.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] He was accused of hypocrisy for not taking a stand on either side, particularly after expressing sentiments at the start of the tour that cricket "has become a synonym for all that is true and honest.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Bradman missed the first Test at Sydney, worn out by constant cricket and the ongoing argument with the Board of Control.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Jardine later wrote that the real reason was that the batsman had suffered a nervous breakdown.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The English bowlers used bodyline intermittently in the first match, to the crowd's vocal displeasure, and the Australians lost the game by ten wickets.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Larwood was particularly successful, returning match figures of ten wickets for 124 runs.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] One of the English bowlers, Gubby Allen, refused to bowl with fielders on the leg side, clashing with Jardine over these tactics.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The only Australian batsman to make an impact was Stan McCabe, who hooked and pulled everything aimed at his upper body, to score 187 not out in four hours from 233 deliveries.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Behind the scenes, administrators began to express concerns to each other.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Yet the English tactics still did not earn universal disapproval; former Australian captain Monty Noble praised the English bowling.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Meanwhile, Woodfull was being encouraged to retaliate to the short-pitched English attack, not least by members of his own side such as Vic Richardson, or to include pace bowlers such as Eddie Gilbert or Laurie Nash to match the aggression of the opposition.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] But Woodfull refused to consider doing so.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] He had to wait until minutes before the game before he was confirmed as captain by the selectors.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] For the second Test, Bradman returned to the team after his newspaper employers released him from his contract.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] England continued to use bodyline and Bradman was dismissed by his first ball in the first innings.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] In the second innings, against the full bodyline attack, he scored an unbeaten century which helped Australia to win the match and level the series at one match each.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Critics began to believe bodyline was not quite the threat that had been perceived and Bradman's reputation, which had suffered slightly with his earlier failures, was restored.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] However, the pitch was slightly slower than others in the series, and Larwood was suffering from problems with his boots which reduced his effectiveness.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The controversy reached its peak during the Third Test at Adelaide.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] On the second day, a Saturday, before a crowd of 50,962 spectators, Australia bowled out England who had batted through the first day.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] In the third over of the Australian innings, Larwood bowled to Woodfull.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The fifth ball narrowly missed Woodfull's head and the final ball, delivered short on the line of middle stump, struck Woodfull over the heart.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The batsman dropped his bat and staggered away holding his chest, bent over in pain.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The England players surrounded Woodfull to offer sympathy but the crowd began to protest noisily.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Jardine called to Larwood: "Well bowled, Harold!" Although the comment was aimed at unnerving Bradman, who was also batting at the time, Woodfull was appalled.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Play resumed after a brief delay, once it was certain the Australian captain was fit to carry on and, since Larwood's over had ended, Woodfull did not have to face the bowling of Allen in the next over.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] However, when Larwood was ready to bowl at Woodfull again, play was halted once more when the fielders were moved into bodyline positions, causing the crowd to protest and call abuse at the England team.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Subsequently, Jardine claimed that Larwood requested a field change, Larwood said that Jardine had done so.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Many commentators condemned the alteration of the field as unsporting, and the angry spectators became extremely volatile.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Jardine, although writing that Woodfull could have retired hurt if he was unfit, later expressed his regret at making the field change at that moment.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The fury of the crowd was such that a riot might have occurred had another incident taken place and several writers suggested that the anger of the spectators was the culmination of feelings built up over the two months that bodyline had developed.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] During the over, another rising Larwood delivery knocked the bat out of Woodfull's hands.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] He batted for 89 minutes, being hit a few more times before Allen bowled him for 22.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Later in the day, Pelham Warner, one of the England managers, visited the Australian dressing room.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] He expressed sympathy to Woodfull but was surprised by the Australian's response.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] According to Warner, Woodfull replied, "I don't want to see you, Mr Warner.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] One is trying to play cricket and the other is not." Fingleton wrote that Woodfull had added, "This game is too good to be spoilt.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] It is time some people got out of it." Woodfull was usually dignified and quietly spoken, making his reaction surprising to Warner and others present.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Warner was so shaken that he was found in tears later that day in his hotel room.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] There was no play on the following day, Sunday being a rest day, but on Monday morning, the exchange between Warner and Woodfull was reported in several Australian newspapers.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The players and officials were horrified that a sensitive private exchange had been reported to the press.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Leaks to the press were practically unknown in 1933.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Warner offered Larwood a reward of one pound if he could dismiss Fingleton in the second innings; Larwood obliged by bowling him for a duck.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Fingleton later claimed that Sydney Sun reporter Claude Corbett had received the information from Bradman; for the rest of their lives, Fingleton and Bradman made claim and counter-claim that the other man was responsible for the leak.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The following day, as Australia faced a large deficit on the first innings, Bert Oldfield played a long innings in support of Bill Ponsford, who scored 85.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] In the course of the innings, the English bowlers used bodyline against him, and he faced several short-pitched deliveries but took several fours from Larwood to move to 41.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Having just conceded a four, Larwood bowled fractionally shorter and slightly slower.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Oldfield attempted to hook but lost sight of the ball and edged it onto his temple; the ball fractured his skull.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Oldfield staggered away and fell to his knees and play stopped as Woodfull came onto the pitch and the angry crowd jeered and shouted, once more reaching the point where a riot seemed likely.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Several English players thought about arming themselves with stumps should the crowd come onto the field.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The ball which injured Oldfield was bowled to a conventional, non-bodyline field; Larwood immediately apologised but Oldfield said that it was his own fault before he was helped back to the dressing room and play continued.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Jardine later secretly sent a telegram of sympathy to Oldfield's wife and arranged for presents to be given to his young daughters.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Not all Australians, including the press and players, believed that the cable should have been sent, particularly immediately following a heavy defeat.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The suggestion of unsportsmanlike behaviour was deeply resented by the MCC, and was one of the worst accusations that could have been levelled at the team at the time.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Additionally, members of the MCC believed that the Australians had over-reacted to the English bowling.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] At this point, the remainder of the series was under threat.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Jardine was shaken by the events and by the hostile reactions to his team.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Stories appeared in the press, possibly leaked by the disenchanted Nawab of Pataudi, about fights and arguments between the England players.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Jardine offered to stop using bodyline if the team did not support him, but after a private meeting (not attended by Jardine or either of the team managers) the players released a statement fully supporting the captain and his tactics.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Even so, Jardine would not have played in the fourth Test without the withdrawal of the "unsportsmanlike" accusation.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The Australian Board met to draft a reply cable, which was sent on 30 January, indicating that they wished the series to continue and offering to postpone consideration of the fairness of bodyline bowling until after the series.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The MCC's reply, on 2 February, suggested that continuing the series would be impossible unless the accusation of unsporting behaviour was withdrawn.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The situation escalated into a diplomatic incident.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Figures high up in both the British and Australian government saw bodyline as potentially fracturing an international relationship that needed to remain strong.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The Governor of South Australia, Alexander Hore-Ruthven, who was in England at the time, expressed his concern to British Secretary of State for Dominion Affairs James Henry Thomas that this would cause a significant impact on trade between the nations.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] The standoff was settled when the Australian prime minister, Joseph Lyons, met with members of the Australian Board and outlined to them the severe economic hardships that could be caused in Australia if the British public boycotted Australian trade.
[src:fielding-cricket/bodyline] Following considerable discussion and debate in the English and Australian press, the Australian Board sent a cable to the MCC which, while maintaining its opposition to bodyline bowling, stated "We do not regard the sportsmanship of your team as being in question".
